# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alkmaar
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The **2000 Summer Olympics**, officially the **Games of the XXVII Olympiad**, officially branded as **Sydney 2000**, and also known as the **Games of the New Millennium**, were an international multi-sport event held from 15 September to 1 October 2000 in Sydney, New South Wales, Australia.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] It marked the second time the Summer Olympics were held in Australia, and in the Southern Hemisphere, the first being in Melbourne, in 1956.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Teams from 199 countries participated in the 2000 Games, which were the first to feature at least 300 events in its official sports program.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The Games were estimated to have cost A$6.6 billion.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] These were the final Olympic Games under the IOC presidency of Juan Antonio Samaranch before the arrival of his successor Jacques Rogge.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The final medal tally at the 2000 Summer Olympics was led by the United States, followed by Russia and China with host Australia in fourth place overall.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Cameroon, Colombia, Latvia, Mozambique, and Slovenia won a gold medal for the first time in their Olympic histories, while Barbados, Kuwait, Kyrgyzstan, Macedonia, Saudi Arabia, and Vietnam won their first-ever Olympic medals.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The 2000 Games received universal acclaim, with the organisation, volunteers, sportsmanship, and Australian public being lauded in the international media.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Bill Bryson of *The Times* called the Sydney Games "one of the most successful events on the world stage", saying that they "couldn't be better".
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] James Mossop of the *Electronic Telegraph* called the Games "such a success that any city considering bidding for future Olympics must be wondering how it can reach the standards set by Sydney", while Jack Todd of the *Montreal Gazette* suggested that the "IOC should quit while it's ahead.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Admit there can never be a better Olympic Games, and be done with it," as "Sydney was both exceptional and the best".
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Australia will host the Summer Olympics in Brisbane in 2032, making it the first Asia-Pacific country to host the Summer Olympics three times.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Sydney won the right to host the Games on 24 September 1993, after being selected over Beijing, Berlin, Istanbul, and Manchester in four rounds of voting, at the 101st IOC Session in Monte Carlo, Monaco.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Beijing would later be selected to host the 2008 Summer Olympics eight years later on 13 July 2001 and the 2022 Winter Olympics twenty-two years later on 31 July 2015.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Brasília, Milan, and Tashkent made bids before deciding to withdraw during the bidding process.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Milan would later be selected to host the 2026 Winter Olympics along with Cortina d'Ampezzo twenty-six years later on 24 June 2019.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The *Oxford Olympics Study 2016* estimates the outturn cost of the Sydney 2000 Summer Olympics at US$5 billion in 2015 dollars and cost overrun at 90% in real terms.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Indirect capital costs are *not* included, such as for road, rail, airport infrastructure, hotel upgrades, or other business investments incurred in preparation for the Games but not directly related to staging the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The cost for Sydney 2000 compares with a cost of US$4.6 billion for Rio 2016, US$40‍–‍44 billion for Beijing 2008, and US$51 billion for Sochi 2014, the most expensive Olympics in history.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The average cost for the Summer Games since 1960 is US$5.2 billion, average cost overrun is 176%.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] In 2000, the Auditor-General of New South Wales reported that the Sydney Games cost A$6.6 billion, with a net cost to the public between A$1.7 and A$2.4 billion.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] In the years leading up to the Games, funds were shifted from education and health programs to cover Olympic expenses.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] It has been estimated that the economic impact of the 2000 Olympics was that A$2.1 billion has been shaved from public consumption.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Economic growth was not stimulated to a net benefit, and, in the years after 2000, foreign tourism to NSW grew by less than tourism to Australia as a whole.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] A "multiplier" effect on broader economic development was not realised, as a simple "multiplier" analysis fails to capture that resources have to be redirected from elsewhere: the building of a stadium is at the expense of other public works such as extensions to hospitals.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Many venues that were constructed in Sydney Olympic Park failed financially in the years immediately following the Olympics to meet the expected bookings to meet upkeep expenses.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] It was only the 2003 Rugby World Cup that reconnected the park back to citizens.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] In recent years, infrastructure costs for some facilities have been of growing concern to the NSW Government, especially facilities in Western Sydney.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Proposed metro and light rail links from Olympic Park to Parramatta have been estimated to cost in the same order of magnitude as the public expenditure on the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Stadium Australia had been considered for demolition in 2017 by then NSW Premier Gladys Berejiklian, citing that the stadium was "built for an Olympics" but not for modern spectators.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The plan was scrapped in 2020 during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The Dunc Gray Velodrome has also struggled to keep up its $500,000-per-year maintenance costs, although it is still used for track cycling events.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Although the Opening Ceremony was not scheduled until 15 September, the football competitions began with preliminary matches on 13 September.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Among the pre-ceremony fixtures, host nation Australia lost 1‍–‍0 to Italy at the Melbourne Cricket Ground, which was the main stadium for the 1956 Melbourne Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony began with a tribute to the pastoral heritage of the Australian stockmen and the importance of the stock horse in Australia's heritage.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] It was produced and filmed by the Sydney Olympic Broadcasting Organisation and the home nation broadcaster Seven Network.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] This was introduced by lone rider Steve Jefferys and his rearing Australian stock horse "Ammo".
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] At the cracking of Jefferys' stockwhip, a further 120 riders entered the stadium, their stock horses performing intricate steps, including forming the five Olympic Rings, sounded by a new version of the song that Bruce Rowland had previously composed for the 1982 film *The Man from Snowy River*.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The Australian National Anthem was sung in the first verse by Human Nature and the second by Julie Anthony.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The cultural segments of the event take place with many aspects of the land and its people: the affinity of the mainly coastal-dwelling Australians with the sea that surrounds the Island Continent.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The indigenous inhabitation of the land, the coming of the First Fleet, the continued immigration from many nations, and the rural industry on which the economy of the nation was built, including a display representing the harshness of rural life based on the paintings of Sir Sidney Nolan.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Two memorable scenes were the representation of the heart of the country by 200 Aboriginal women from Central Australia who danced up "the mighty spirit of god to protect the Games" and the overwhelmingly noisy representation of the construction industry by hundreds of tap-dancing teenagers.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] A record 199 nations entered the stadium, with a record 80 of them winning at least one medal.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The only missing IOC member was Afghanistan, which was banned due to the extremist rule of the Taliban's oppression of women and its prohibition of sports.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The ceremony featured a unified entrance by the athletes of North and South Korea, using a specially designed unification flag: a white background flag with a blue map of the Korean Peninsula.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Four athletes from East Timor also marched in the parade of nations as individual Olympic athletes and marched directly before the host country.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Although the country-to-be had no National Olympic Committee then, they were allowed to compete under the Olympic Flag with country code IOA.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The Governor-General, Sir William Deane, opened the games.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The Olympic Flag was carried around the arena by eight former Australian Olympic champions: Bill Roycroft, Murray Rose, Liane Tooth, Gillian Rolton, Marjorie Jackson, Lorraine Crapp, Michael Wenden and Nick Green.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] During the raising of the Olympics Flag, the Olympic Hymn was sung by the Millennium Choir of the Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of Australia in Greek.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Following this, Tina Arena sang a purpose-written pop song, *The Flame*.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony concluded with the lighting of the Olympic Flame, which was brought into the stadium by former Australian Olympic champion Herb Elliott.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The choice of Freeman, an Aboriginal woman, to light the flame was notable given the history of human rights abuses against Aboriginal people in Australia.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Following her lighting, Freeman was the subject of racial abuse from some Australians.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The planned spectacular climax to the ceremony was delayed by the technical glitch of a computer switch which malfunctioned, causing the sequence to shut down by giving a false reading.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] This meant that the Olympic flame was suspended in mid-air for about four minutes rather than immediately rising up a water-covered ramp to the top of the stadium.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] When the cause of the problem was discovered, the program was overridden and the cauldron continued its course, and the ceremony concluded with a fireworks display.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The first medals of the Games were awarded in the women's 10-metre air rifle competition, which was won by Nancy Johnson of the United States.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The triathlon made its Olympic debut with the women's race.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Set in the surroundings of the Sydney Opera House, Brigitte McMahon representing Switzerland swam, cycled and ran to the first gold medal in the sport, beating the favoured home athletes such as Michelie Jones who won silver.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] McMahon only passed Jones in sight of the finish line.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The first star of the Games was 17-year-old Australian Ian Thorpe, who first set a new world record in the 400-metre freestyle final before competing in an exciting 4 × 100 m freestyle final.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Swimming the last leg, Thorpe passed the leading American team and arrived in a new world record time, two-tenths of a second ahead of the Americans.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] In the same event for women, the Americans also broke the world record, finishing ahead of the Netherlands and Sweden.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Samaranch had to leave for home, as his wife was severely ill.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Upon arrival, his wife had already died.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Samaranch returned to Sydney four days later.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The Olympic flag was flown at half-staff during the period as a sign of respect to Samaranch's wife.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Canadian Simon Whitfield sprinted away in the last 100 metres of the men's triathlon, becoming the inaugural winner in the event.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] On the cycling track, Robert Bartko beat fellow German Jens Lehmann in the individual pursuit, setting a new Olympic Record.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Leontien Zijlaard-van Moorsel set a world record in the semi-finals the same event for women.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] In the swimming pool, American Tom Dolan beat the world record in the 400-metre medley, successfully defending the title he won in Atlanta four years prior.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Dutchwoman Inge de Bruijn also clocked a new world record, beating her own time in the 100 m butterfly final to win by more than a second.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The main event for the Australians on the fourth day of the Games was the 200 m freestyle.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Dutchman Pieter van den Hoogenband had broken the world record in the semi-finals, taking it from the new Australian hero Ian Thorpe, who came close to the world record in his semi-final heat.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] As the final race finished, Van den Hoogenband's time was exactly the same as in the semi-finals, finishing ahead of Thorpe by half a second.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] China won the gold medal in the men's team all-around gymnastics competition after being the runner-up in the previous two Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The other medals were taken by Ukraine and Russia, respectively.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Zijlaard-van Moorsel lived up to the expectations set by her world record in cycling in the semis by winning the gold medal.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] During the Women's Gymnastics All-Around, female athletes suffered damning scores and injuries due to improperly installed gymnastics equipment.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Gymnasts performing on the vault gave uncharacteristically poor performances and fell.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Officials blamed the series of falls and low scores on performance anxiety.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] It was not until Australian gymnast Allana Slater and her coach, Peggy Liddick, voiced concerns about the equipment that officials discovered the apparatus was five centimetres, or almost two inches, lower than it should have been.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] While athletes were given the opportunity to perform again, for some of them, the damage to their mental or physical health caused by the vault was irreparable.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Chinese gymnast Kui Yuanyuan and American gymnast Kristen Maloney both injured their legs while attempting to stick their landings, with Kui needing to be carried to an examination area and Maloney damaging a titanium rod that had recently been implanted in her shin.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Romanian gymnast Andreea Răducan ultimately took gold while her teammates, Simona Amânar and Maria Olaru took silver and bronze, respectively.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] By rowing in the winning coxless four, Steve Redgrave of Great Britain became a member of a select group who had won gold medals at five consecutive Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The swimming 4 x 100-metre medley relay of B.J.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Bedford, Megan Quann (Jendrick), Jenny Thompson and Dara Torres became the first women's relay team to finish in under four minutes, swimming 3:58 and setting a world record, claiming the gold medal for the United States.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Rulon Gardner, never an NCAA champion or a world medalist, beat Alexander Karelin of Russia to win gold in the super heavyweight class, Greco-Roman wrestling.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Karelin had won gold in Seoul, Barcelona and Atlanta.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Before this fight, he had never lost in international competition, had been unbeaten in all competitions in thirteen years, and had not surrendered a point in a decade.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Australian Cathy Freeman won the 400-metre final in front of a jubilant Sydney crowd at the Olympic Stadium, ahead of Lorraine Graham of Jamaica and Katharine Merry of Great Britain.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Freeman's win made her the first competitor in Olympic Games history to light the Olympic Flame and then go on to win a gold medal.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The attendance at the stadium was 112,524 – the largest attendance for any sport in Olympic Games history.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] In a men's basketball pool match between the United States and France, the USA's Vince Carter made one of the most famous dunks in basketball history.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] After getting the ball off a steal, the 6'6"/1.98 m Carter drove to the basket, with 7'2"/2.18 m centre Frédéric Weis in his way.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Carter jumped, spread his legs in midair, scraped Weis' head on the way up, and dunked.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The French media dubbed the feat *le dunk de la mort* ("the dunk of death").
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The Canadian flag at the athletes' village was lowered to half-mast, as Canadian athletes paid tribute to the former prime minister Pierre Trudeau after hearing of his death in Montreal (because of the time zone difference, it was 29 September in Sydney when Trudeau died).
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The Canadian flag was flown at half-mast for the remainder of the Olympics, on orders from both IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch and Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The state funeral took place on 3 October, two days after the closing ceremony, allowing enough time for those concerned to head back to Canada after the Games and attend his funeral.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Cameroon won a historic gold medal over Spain in the Men's Olympic Football Final at the Olympic Stadium.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The game went to a penalty shootout, which was won by Cameroon 5‍–‍3.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The last event of the Games was the Men's Marathon, contested on a course that started in North Sydney.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The event was won by Ethiopian Gezahegne Abera, with Kenyan Erick Wainaina second, and Tesfaye Tola, also of Ethiopia, third.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] It was the first time since the 1968 Olympics that an Ethiopian won the gold medal in this event.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The closing ceremony commenced with Christine Anu performing her version of the Warumpi Band's song "My Island Home", with several Aboriginal dancers atop the Geodome Stage in the middle of the stadium, around which several hundred umbrella and lamp box kids created an image of Aboriginal Dreamtime.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The Geodome Stage was used throughout the ceremony, which was a flat stage mechanically raised into the shape of a geode.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Although demonstration sports were abolished following the 1992 Summer Olympics, the Sydney Olympics featured wheelchair racing as exhibition events on the athletics schedule.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Special quarantine conditions were introduced to allow entry of horses into Australia to participate in equestrian events, avoiding the need for such events to take place elsewhere as had happened at the 1956 Summer Olympics in Melbourne.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] 199 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) participated in the Sydney Games, two more than in the 1996 Summer Olympics; in addition, there were four Timorese Individual Olympic Athletes.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Eritrea, the Federated States of Micronesia and Palau made their Olympic debut this year.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Democratic Republic of the Congo was once again designated under that name, after it participated as Zaire from 1984 to 1996.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Afghanistan was the only 1996 participant (and the only existing NOC) that did not participate in the 2000 Olympics, having been banned due to the Taliban's totalitarian rule in Afghanistan, their oppression of women, and its prohibition of sports.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] 10,647 athletes from 199 NOCs participated in the 2000 Summer Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals in the 2000 Games.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The ranking in this table is based on information provided by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Some other sources may be inconsistent due to not taking into account all later doping cases.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] A number of quasi-government bodies were responsible for the construction, organisation and execution of the Sydney Games.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] These bodies are often collectively referred to as the "Olympic Family".
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The organisation of the 2000 Summer Paralympics was the responsibility of the Sydney Paralympic Organising Committee (SPOC).
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] However, much of the planning and operation of the Paralympic Games was outsourced to SOCOG such that most operational programmes planned both the Olympic and Paralympic Games.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The internal organisation of SOCOG evolved over the phases of the project and changed, sometimes radically, several times.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] In late 1998, the design was principally functional.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The top two tiers below the CEO Sandy Hollway consisted of five groups (managed by Group General Managers and the Deputy CEO) and twenty divisions (managed by divisional General Managers), which in turn were further broken up into programmes and sub-programmes or projects.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] In 1999, functional areas (FAs) broke up into geographic precinct and venue teams (managed by Precinct Managers and Venue Managers) with functional area staff reporting to both the FA manager and the venue manager.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The Interstate Football division extant in 1998 was the first of these geographically based venue teams.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The origins of the volunteer program for Sydney 2000 dates back to the bid, as early as 1992.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] On 17 December 1992, a group of Sydney citizens interested in the prospect of hosting the 2000 Olympic and Paralympic Games gathered for a meeting at Sports House at Wentworth Park in Sydney.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] In the period leading up to 1999, after Sydney had won the bid, the small group of volunteers grew from approximately 42 to around 500.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] These volunteers became known as Pioneer Volunteers.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The Pioneer Volunteer program was managed internally by SOCOG's Volunteer Services Department in consultation with prominent peak groups like The Centre for Volunteering (Volunteering and TAFE.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Some of the Pioneer Volunteers still meet every four months, an unseen legacy of the Games which brought together a community spirit not seen before.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] During the Olympic games, tens of thousands of volunteers (the official figure placed at 46,967) helped everywhere at the Olympic venues and elsewhere in the city.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] They were honoured with a parade like the athletes had a few days before.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The original festivals in Olympia celebrated both cultural events and physical feats.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The tradition continued with the first modern Olympics in 1896, and since then various cultural events have accompanied the sporting competition.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Starting with the 1996 Summer Olympics, a cycle of four arts festivals have been staged by each host country.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The Sydney Olympic Arts Festival was an arts festival that ran before and during the Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The festival event coordinator was David Gallen.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The first of the four festivals was the first edition of the Festival of the Dreaming, which was founded by artistic director Rhoda Roberts (who later co-directed segments of the Opening Ceremony), was held in 1997, as the first of four leading up to the Sydney Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Some events were held at the Sydney Opera House, and the festival included an Aboriginal cast performing Shakespeare's *A Midsummer Night's Dream*, as well as Samuel Beckett's *Waiting for Godot* performed in the Bundjalung language.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The second festival was "A Sea Change", in which artists and companies from Australia and Oceania explored "the influence of the sea on Australian life as a means to explore the changing political and cultural climates in Australia".
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The fourth and final festival, while featuring many international artists and companies, served as a showcase for the diversity and depth of the arts in Australia.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Opening four weeks before the Olympic Games, the Sydney 2000 Olympics Arts Festival ran until the last day of athletic competition, from 18 August to 1 October 2000.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Starting with an all-day Aboriginal welcoming ceremony, *Tubowgule* ("the Meeting of the Waters"), choreographed by Stephen Page, began at La Perouse beach near Botany Bay, and concluded at Bennelong Point, in the forecourt of Sydney Opera House.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] There, contemporary Indigenous dance company Bangarra Dance Theatre performed *Energy of Australia*.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The gala opening event for the festival was the musically pyrotechnical "Symphony of a Thousand" by Mahler at the Sydney SuperDome.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The festival included many performing arts events, mostly presented at the Sydney Opera House.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] There were also dance, singing, and drama performances, staged mainly at the Opera House but also at Her Majesty's Theatre and the Capitol Theatre.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] Only two plush toys of Fatso were made, one of which was placed in the Olympic Village; the plush was controversially smuggled into a medal ceremony by the Australian men's 4 × 200-metre relay team.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The character achieved a cult following, with some Australians preferring Fatso to the actual mascots.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] One of the Fatso plushes was auctioned for charity following the Games (being sold to Kerry Stokes, an executive of the Seven Network, for A$80,450), while a figure of Fatso was included in an display outside Stadium Australia that commemorated the Games' volunteers.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] A total of 750 gold, 750 silver and 780 bronze medals were minted for the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The gold and silver medals contained 99.99 percent of pure silver.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The bronze medals were 99 percent bronze with one percent silver, they were made by melting down Australian one-cent and two-cent coins, which had been removed from circulation from 1992 onward.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The bouquets handed to medal recipients incorporated foliage from the Grevillea baileyana, also known as the white oak.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee awarded Sydney and its inhabitants with the "Pierre de Coubertin Trophy" in recognition of the collaboration and happiness shown by the people of Sydney during the event to all the athletes and visitors around the world.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] After the Games had ended, the New South Wales Police Force was granted use of the Olympic Rings in a new commendation and citation as the IOC consideration after having staged the "safest" Games ever.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] The Australian Entertainment Mo Awards (commonly known informally as the Mo Awards), were annual Australian entertainment industry awards.
[src:alkmaar/2000-summer-olympics] They recognise achievements in live entertainment in Australia from 1975 to 2016.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Games saw 10,625 athletes compete, some 600 more than expected, accompanied by 5,501 team officials from 201 countries, with 301 medal events in 28 different sports.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Athens became the fourth city to host the Summer Olympic Games on two occasions (together with Paris, London and Los Angeles).
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] A new medal obverse was introduced at these Games, replacing the design by Giuseppe Cassioli that had been used since 1928.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The new design features the Panathenaic Stadium in Athens rectifying the long-running mistake of using a depiction of the Roman Colosseum rather than a Greek venue.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The 2004 Olympic Games were hailed as "unforgettable dream games" by then-IOC president Jacques Rogge, and left Athens with a significantly improved infrastructure, including a new airport, ring road and subway system.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] There has been debate (mostly in popular media) regarding the cost of the Games and their possible contribution to the 2010–18 Greek government-debt crisis, although there is little or no evidence supporting this claim.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The 2004 Games were generally deemed to be a success, with the rising standard of competition amongst nations across the world.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The final medal tally was led by the United States, followed by China and Russia with host nation Greece in 15th place.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Several world and Olympic records were also broken during these Games.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Chile, Chinese Taipei, Dominican Republic, Georgia and Israel won their first Olympic gold medals.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Eritrea and Paraguay won their first Olympic medals.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The United Arab Emirates (UAE) won both their first Olympic medal and gold medal in this event.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Athens was chosen as the host city during the 106th IOC Session held in Lausanne, Switzerland, on 5 September 1997.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Greek capital had lost its bid to organize the 1996 Summer Olympics to the American city of Atlanta nearly seven years before, during the 96th IOC Session in Tokyo, Japan on 18 September 1990.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Under the direction of Gianna Angelopoulos-Daskalaki, Athens pursued another bid, this time for the right to host the Summer Olympics in 2004.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Unlike the 1996 bid that was seen arrogant when the city was bidding, the 2004 bid was lauded for its low scale, humility, honest and earnestness, its focused message, and a more real and detailed bid concept.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] During the unsuccessful 1996 bid, concerns and criticisms were raised – primarily regarding critical subjects about the city's infrastructural readiness, its air pollution, its budget and politicization of the Games' events and their preparations.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Another factor that contributed to the Greek capital's selection was a growing sentiment among some IOC members to restore some original values of the Olympics to the Modern Games, a component which they felt was lost during the 1996 Summer Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] After leading all voting rounds, Athens easily defeated Rome in the fifth and final vote.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Cape Town, Stockholm, and Buenos Aires (the latter won the rights to host the 2018 Summer Youth Olympics in 2013), the three other cities that made the IOC shortlist, were eliminated in prior rounds of voting.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Six other cities submitted applications, but their bids were dropped by the IOC in 1996.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] These cities were Istanbul, Lille, Rio de Janeiro (the latter won the rights to host the 2016 Summer Olympics in 2009), San Juan, Seville, and Saint Petersburg.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The 2004 Summer Olympic Games cost the Government of Greece near €9 billion to stage.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Athens 2004 Organizing Committee (ATHOC), responsible for the preparation and organisation of the Games, concluded its operations as a company in 2005 with a surplus of €130.6 million.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The State's contribution to the total ATHOC budget was 8% of its expenditure against an originally anticipated 14%.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The overall revenue of ATHOC, including income from tickets, sponsors, broadcasting rights, merchandise sales etc., totalled near €2.1 billion.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The largest percentage of that income (38%) came from media rights.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] According to the cost-benefit evaluation of the impact of the Athens 2004 Olympic Games presented to the Greek Parliament in January 2013 by the Minister of Finance Mr.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Giannis Stournaras, the overall net economic benefit for Greece was positive.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Greek Ministry of Finance reported in 2013 that the expenses of the Greek state for the Athens 2004 Olympic and Paralympic Games, including both infrastructure and organizational costs, reached the amount of €8.5 billion.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The same report further explains that €2 billion of this amount was covered by the revenue of the ATHOC (from tickets, sponsors, broadcasting rights, merchandise sales etc.) and that another €2 billion was directly invested in upgrading hospitals and preserving archaeological sites.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Therefore, the net infrastructure costs related to the preparation of the Athens 2004 Olympic Games was €4.5 billion, substantially lower than the reported estimates, and mainly included long-standing fixed asset investments in numerous municipal and transport infrastructures.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] On the revenue side, the same report estimates that incremental tax revenues of approximately €3.5 billion arose from the increased activities caused by the Athens 2004 Olympic Games during the period 2000 to 2004.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] These tax revenues were paid directly to the Greek state specifically in the form of incremental social security contributions, income taxes and VAT tax paid by all the companies, professionals, and service providers that were directly involved with the Olympic Games.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Cost per sporting event for Athens 2004 was US$9.8 million.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] This compares with US$14.9 million for Rio 2016, US$49.5 million for London 2012, and US$22.5 million for Beijing 2008.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Average cost per event for the Summer Games since 1960 is US$19.9 million.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Cost per athlete for Athens 2004 was US$0.3 million.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] This compares with US$0.4 million for Rio 2016, US$1.4 million for London 2012, and US$0.6 million for Beijing 2008.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Average cost per athlete for the Summer Games since 1960 is US$0.6 million.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Cost overrun for Athens 2004 was 49%, measured in real terms from the bid to host the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] This compares with 51% for Rio 2016 and 76% for London 2012.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Average cost overrun for the Summer Games since 1960 is 176%.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] By late March 2004, some Olympic projects were still behind schedule, and Greek authorities announced that a roof it had initially proposed as an optional, non-vital addition to the Aquatics Center would no longer be built.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The main Olympic Stadium, the designated facility for the opening and closing ceremonies, was completed only two months before the Games opened.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] This stadium was completed with a retractable glass roof designed by Spanish architect Santiago Calatrava.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The same architect also designed the Velodrome and other facilities.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Infrastructure, such as the tram line linking venues in southern Athens with the city centre, and numerous venues were considerably behind schedule just two months before the start of the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The subsequent pace of preparation, however, made the rush to finish the Athens venues one of the tightest in Olympics history.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Greeks, unperturbed, maintained that they would make it all along.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] By July/August 2004, all venues were delivered: in August, the Olympic Stadium was officially completed and opened, joined or preceded by the official completion and openings of other venues within the Athens Olympic Sports Complex (OAKA), and the sports complexes in Faliro and Helliniko.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Late July and early August witnessed the Athens Tram become operational, and this system provided additional connections to those already existing between Athens city centre and its waterfront communities along the Saronic Gulf.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The upgrades to the Athens Metro were also completed, and the new lines became operational by mid-summer.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] EMI released *Unity*, the official pop album of the Athens Olympics, in the leadup to the Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] It features contributions from Sting, Lenny Kravitz, Moby, Destiny's Child, and Avril Lavigne.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] EMI has pledged to donate US$180,000 from the album to UNICEF's HIV/AIDS program in Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] At least 14 people died during the work on the facilities.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Most of these people were not from Greece.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Before the Games, Greek hotel staff staged a series of one-day strikes over wage disputes.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] They had been asking for a significant raise for the period covering the event being staged.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Paramedics and ambulance drivers also protested.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] They claimed to have the right to the same Olympic bonuses promised to their security force counterparts.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Panorama of Athens Olympic Sports Complex.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The lighting ceremony of the Olympic flame took place on 25 March 2004 in Ancient Olympia.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] For the first time ever, the flame travelled around the world in a relay to various Summer Olympic host cities (past and future) and other large cities, before returning to Greece.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Athens Olympic Broadcasting served as the host broadcaster for the Games, providing over 35,000 hours of coverage to over 300 television channels around the world.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Local rights to the Games were held by ERT which devoted their three channels (ET1, NET and ET3) to more than 24 hours of Olympic coverage.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] For the first time, major broadcasters were allowed to serve video coverage of the Olympics over the Internet, provided that they restricted this service geographically, to protect broadcasting contracts in other areas.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The International Olympic Committee forbade Olympic athletes, as well as coaches, support personnel and other officials, from setting up specialized weblogs or other websites for covering their personal perspective of the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] They were not allowed to post audio, video, or photos that they had taken.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] An exception was made if an athlete already has a personal website that was not set up specifically for the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] NBC launched its own Olympic website, NBCOlympics.com.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Focusing on the television coverage of the Games, it did provide video clips, medal standings, live results.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Its main purpose, however, was to provide a schedule of what sports were on the many stations of NBC Universal.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Games were shown on television 24 hours a day, on one network or another.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The medals awarded during the 2004 Summer Olympics introduced a redesigned obverse for Olympic medals, marking the first major change to the standard design since the 1928 Summer Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Organizers stated that the redesign was intended to emphasize the Greek heritage of the Olympic Games and their revival in the modern era.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Previous Olympic medals, used from 1928 through the 2000 Summer Olympics, depicted the goddess Nike seated while holding an ear of corn and a wreath.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] For Athens 2004, Nike was instead portrayed flying into the stadium to deliver victory to the winning athlete.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Panathenaic Stadium, the venue of the first modern Olympic Games in 1896, was also depicted on the obverse side, alongside an engraving identifying the athlete’s sporting discipline.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The medals were designed by Elena Votsi and produced by Efsimon.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The medals had a diameter of 60 millimetres and were awarded in gold, silver and bronze compositions corresponding to first, second and third place respectively.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The podiums used during the 2004 Summer Olympics incorporated elements of the “Panorama” visual identity developed for the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The “Panorama” design reflected aspects of Greek culture, language and landscape, drawing inspiration from the colours of the sea and the tones of the country’s olive groves.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] During the 2004 Summer Olympics, medal-winning athletes standing on the podium were crowned with olive wreaths, referencing traditions associated with the ancient Olympic Games.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] As with any enterprise, the Organizing Committee and everyone involved with it relied heavily on technology in order to deliver a successful event.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] ATHOC maintained two separate data networks, one for the preparation of the Games (known as the Administrative network) and one for the Games themselves (Games Network).
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] This infrastructure was created and maintained to serve directly more than 150,000 ATHOC Staff, Volunteers, Olympic family members (IOC, NOCs, Federations), Partners & Sponsors and Media.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] It also kept the information flowing for all spectators, TV viewers, Website visitors and news readers around the world, prior and during the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Media Center was located inside the Zappeion which is a Greek national exhibition center.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Between June and August 2004, the technology staff worked in the Technology Operations Center (TOC) from where it could centrally monitor and manage all the devices and flow of information, as well as handle any problems that occurred during the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Systems, Telecommunications, Information Security, Data Network, Staffing, etc.) under a TOC Director and corresponding team leaders (Shift Managers).
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The TOC operated on a 24x7 basis with personnel organized into 12-hour shifts.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony of the games, directed by choreographer Dimitris Papaioannou and produced by Jack Morton Worldwide, led by project director David Zolkwer, was held on 13 August 2004.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] It began with a twenty-eight (the number of the Olympiads up to then) second countdown paced by the sounds of an amplified heartbeat.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] As the countdown was completed, fireworks rumbled and illuminated the skies overhead.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] After a drum corps and bouzouki players joined in an opening march, the video screen showed images of flight, crossing southwest from Athens over the Greek countryside to ancient Olympia.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Then, a single drummer in the ancient stadium joined in a drum duet with a single drummer in the main stadium in Athens, joining the original ancient Olympic Games with the modern ones in symbolism.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] At the end of the drum duet, a single flaming arrow was launched from the video screen (symbolically from ancient Olympia) and into the reflecting pool, which resulted in fire erupting in the middle of the stadium creating a burning image of the Olympic rings rising from the pool.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Opening Ceremony was a pageant of traditional Greek culture and history hearkening back to its mythological beginnings.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The program began as a young Greek boy sailed into the stadium on a 'paper-ship' waving the host nation's flag to aethereal music by Manos Hatzidakis and then a centaur appeared, followed by a gigantic head of a cycladic figurine which eventually broke into many pieces symbolising the Greek islands.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Underneath the cycladic head was a Hellenistic representation of the human body, reflecting the concept and belief in perfection reflected in Greek art.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] A man was seen balancing on a hovering cube symbolising man's eternal 'split' between passion and reason followed by a couple of young lovers playfully chasing each other while the god Eros was hovering above them.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] There followed a very colourful float parade chronicling Greek history from the ancient Minoan civilization to modern times.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Also, lower frontal nudity of men dressed as ancient Greek statues was shown in such a way that the area below the waist was cut off by the bottom of the screen.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Overall, NBC's coverage of the Olympics has been praised, and the company was awarded with 6 Emmy Awards for its coverage of the Games and technical production.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Additionally, NBC televised all 28 sports in the 2004 Games, becoming the first broadcaster to do so.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Following the artistic performances, a parade of nations entered the stadium with over 10,500 athletes walking under the banners of 201 nations.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The nations were arranged according to Greek alphabet making the Philippines, Finland, Fiji, Chile, and Hong Kong the last five to enter the stadium before the Greek delegation.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] On this occasion, in observance of the tradition that the delegation of Greece opens the parade and the host nation closes it, the Greek flag bearer opened the parade and all the Greek delegation closed it.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Based on audience reaction, the emotional high point of the parade was the entrance of the delegation from Afghanistan which had been absent from the Olympics and had female competitors for the first time.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Iraqi delegation also stirred emotions.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Also recognized was the symbolic unified march of athletes from North Korea and South Korea under the Korean Unification Flag.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The country of Kiribati made its debut appearance at these Games and East Timor made a debut under its own flag.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] After the Parade of Nations, during which the Dutch DJ Tiësto provided the music, the Icelandic singer Björk performed the song "Oceania", written specially for the event by her and the poet Sjón.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony culminated in the lighting of the Olympic cauldron by 1996 gold medalist windsurfer Nikolaos Kaklamanakis.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Many key moments in the ceremony, including the lighting of the Olympic Cauldron, featured music composed and arranged by New Zealand composer John Psathas.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The gigantic cauldron, which was styled after the Athens 2004 Olympic torch, pivoted down to be lit by the 35-year-old, before slowly swinging up and lifting the flame above the stadium.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Following this, a fireworks display commenced to conclude the ceremony.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] All National Olympic Committees (NOCs) except Djibouti participated in the Athens Games.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Two new NOCs had been created since 2000 and made their debut at these Games (Kiribati and East Timor).
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Therefore, with the return of Afghanistan (who had been banned from the 2000 Summer Olympics), the number of participating nations increased from 199 to 201.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Additionally, Yugoslavia had changed its name the year prior to Serbia and Montenegro and its code from YUG to SCG; the country would dissolve two years later, making this its only Olympics appearance under the new moniker.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Georgia's new flag made its debut at the Olympics by unfurling it at the opening ceremony on 13 August.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] It replaces the post-Soviet flag, which had been used since Lillehammer 1994.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] In the table below, the number in parentheses indicates the number of participants contributed by each NOC.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] 10,557 athletes from 201 NOCs participated in the 2004 Summer Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The sports featured at the 2004 Summer Olympics are listed below.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Officially there were 301 events in 28 sports as swimming, diving, synchronised swimming and water polo are classified by the IOC as disciplines within the sport of aquatics, and wheelchair racing was a demonstration sport.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] For the first time, the wrestling category featured women's wrestling and in the fencing competition women competed in the sabre.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] American Kristin Heaston, who led off the qualifying round of women's shot put became the first woman to compete at the ancient site of Olympia.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The demonstration sport of wheelchair racing was a joint Olympic/Paralympic event, allowing a Paralympic event to occur within the Olympics, and for the future, opening up the wheelchair race to the able-bodied.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The 2004 Summer Paralympics were also held in Athens, from 17 to 28 September.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Games were concluded on 29 August 2004.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The closing ceremony was held at the Athens Olympic Stadium, where the Games had been opened 16 days earlier.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Around 70,000 people gathered in the stadium to watch the ceremony.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The initial part of the ceremony interspersed the performances of various Greek singers, and featured traditional Greek dance performances from various regions of Greece (Crete, Thessaly, etc.).
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The event was meant to highlight the pride of the Greeks in their culture and country for the world to see.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] A significant part of the closing ceremony was the exchange of the Olympic flag of the Athens Games between the mayor of Athens and the mayor of Beijing, host city of the next Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] After the flag exchange a presentation from the Beijing delegation presented a glimpse into Chinese culture for the world to see.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The medal ceremony for the last event of the Olympics, the men's marathon, was conducted, with Stefano Baldini from Italy as the winner.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The bronze medal winner, Vanderlei Cordeiro de Lima of Brazil, was simultaneously announced as a recipient of the Pierre de Coubertin Medal for his bravery in finishing the race despite being attacked by a rogue spectator while leading with 7 km to go.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] A flag-bearer from each nation's delegation then entered along the stage, followed by the competitors *en masse* on the floor.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] All of them were led by Pyrros Dimas (weightlifter) and Liu Xiang (hurdler).
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Short speeches were presented by Gianna Angelopoulos-Daskalaki, President of the Organising Committee, and by President Dr.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Jacques Rogge of the IOC, in which he described the Athens Olympics as "unforgettable, dream Games".
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Rogge had previously declared he would be breaking with tradition in his closing speech as President of the IOC and that he would never use the words of his predecessor Juan Antonio Samaranch, who used to always say 'these were the best ever games'.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The national anthems of Greece and China were played in a handover ceremony as both nations' flags were raised.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Mayor of Athens, Dora Bakoyianni, passed the Olympic Flag to the Mayor of Beijing, Wang Qishan.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] After a short cultural performance by Chinese actors, dancers, and musicians directed by eminent Chinese director Zhang Yimou, Rogge declared the 2004 Olympic Games closed.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic flag was next raised again on 10 February 2006 during the opening ceremony of the next Winter Olympics in Torino.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] A young Greek girl, 10-year-old Fotini Papaleonidopoulou, lit a symbolic lantern with the Olympic Flame and passed it on to other children before "extinguishing" the flame in the cauldron by blowing a puff of air.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] These are the top ten nations that won medals in the 2004 Games.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Facilities of the 2004 Summer Olympics in the Greater Athens area.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p02] Mascots have been a tradition at the Olympic Games since the 1968 Winter Olympics in Grenoble, France.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p02] The 2004 Olympics had two official mascots: *Athena* and *Phevos* (Greek pronunciation: Athina and Fivos).
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p02] The sister and brother were named after Athena, the goddess of wisdom, strategy and Phoebus, the god of light and music, respectively.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p02] They were inspired by the ancient daidala, which were toy dolls that also had religious connotations.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p02] To commemorate the 2004 Olympics, a series of Greek high value euro collectors' coins were minted by the Mint of Greece, in both silver and gold.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p02] The pieces depict landmarks in Greece as well as ancient and modern sports on the obverse of the coin.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p02] On the reverse, a common motif with the logo of the Games, circled by an olive branch representing the spirit of the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p02] Preparations to stage the Olympics led to a number of positive developments for the city's infrastructure.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p02] All of the above infrastructure is still in use to this day, and there have been continued expansions and proposals to expand Athens' metro, tram, suburban rail and motorway network, the airport, as well as further plans to pedestrianize more thoroughfares in the historic center of Athens.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p02] As of 2012 many conversion schemes have stalled owing to the Greek government-debt crisis, though many of these facilities are now under the control of domestic sporting clubs and organizations or the private sector.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p02] The Hellinikon Olympic Complex saw multiple venues demolished and the park is being transformed into Hellinikon Metropolitan Park which will become home to Hard Rock Hotel & Casino Athens, the first integrated resort in Greece.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p02] There have been arguments (mostly in popular media) that the cost of the 2004 Athens Summer Games was a contributor to the Greek government-debt crisis that started in 2010, while a lot of focus has been on the use of the facilities after the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p02] Furthermore, the aforementioned arguments do not even take into account the profits (direct and indirect) generated by the Games, which may well have surpassed the above costs.
[src:alkmaar/2004-summer-olympics-p02] Finally, popular arguments about "rotting" of many of the facilities, appear to ignore the actual utilization of many of these structures.
[src:alkmaar/2008-09-eredivisie] The **2008–09 Eredivisie** was the 53rd season of Eredivisie since its establishment in 1955.
[src:alkmaar/2008-09-eredivisie] The season began on 29 August 2008 with a game between Vitesse Arnhem and FC Groningen and ended on 10 May 2009.
[src:alkmaar/2008-09-eredivisie] A total of 18 teams take part in the league, consisting of 16 who competed in the previous season and two promoted from the Eerste Divisie.
[src:alkmaar/2008-09-eredivisie] The teams promoted from the Eerste Divisie at the end of the previous season were champions FC Volendam, and play-off winners ADO Den Haag.
[src:alkmaar/2008-09-eredivisie] AZ clinched their second title, their first coming in 1981.
[src:alkmaar/2008-09-eredivisie] Rules for classification: 1) points; 2) goal difference; 3) number of goals scored.
[src:alkmaar/2008-09-eredivisie] Legend: Blue = home team win; Yellow = draw; Red = away team win.
[src:alkmaar/2008-09-eredivisie] Contrary to the play-offs of previous years, only teams placed 6th through 9th compete in a play-off tournament for one spot in the second qualifying round of the UEFA Europa League 2009–10.
[src:alkmaar/2008-09-eredivisie] The 16th and 17th placed teams, along with the teams from Eerste Divisie, participate in a play-off for two spots in 2009–10 Eredivisie.
[src:alkmaar/2008-09-eredivisie] RKC Waalwijk and Roda JC will play in Eredivisie 2009–10.
[src:alkmaar/2008-09-eredivisie] The Dutch public broadcaster NOS broadcast the match highlights after beating rival broadcaster RTL for the contract.
[src:alkmaar/2008-09-eredivisie] The new pay-per-view channel Eredivisie Live broadcast the live matches.
[src:alkmaar/2008-09-eredivisie] In Australia the Eredivisie was broadcast live and exclusive by Setanta Sports.
[src:alkmaar/2010-european-athletics-championships] The **2010 European Athletics Championships** were the 20th edition of the European Athletics Championships, organised under the supervision of the European Athletic Association.
[src:alkmaar/2010-european-athletics-championships] They were held at the Estadi Olímpic Lluís Companys in Barcelona, Catalonia, Spain from 27 July to 1 August 2010.
[src:alkmaar/2010-european-athletics-championships] Barcelona was the first Spanish city to host the European Championships.
[src:alkmaar/2010-european-athletics-championships] Barni was the mascot of the event, he was the main promotional tool of the Championship.
[src:alkmaar/2010-european-athletics-championships] His name comes from Barna and was designed by the workshop Dortoka.
[src:alkmaar/2010-european-athletics-championships] 1 Stanislav Emelyanov of Russia originally won the 20 km walk gold medal with a time of 1:20:10, but he was disqualified in 2014 after he tested positive for drugs.
[src:alkmaar/2010-european-athletics-championships] 2 Andrei Mikhnevich of Belarus originally won the gold medal in 21.01 m, but was disqualified in 2013 (all his results starting from the 2005 World Championships were canceled).
[src:alkmaar/2010-european-athletics-championships] The women's medal standings were significantly altered after various post-race doping controversies.
[src:alkmaar/2010-european-athletics-championships] The following medals were revoked years after the event for doping cases, and assigned to the athletes who followed in the ranking.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The **2012 Summer Olympics**, officially the **Games of the XXX Olympiad** and also known as **London 2012**, were an international multi-sport event held from 27 July to 12 August 2012 in London, England.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Some events were held at venues elsewhere in the United Kingdom.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There were 10,518 athletes from 206 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) who participated in the 2012 Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Following a bid headed by the former Olympic champion Sebastian Coe and the mayor of London, Ken Livingstone, London was selected as the host city at the 117th IOC Session in Singapore on 6 July 2005, defeating bids from Moscow, New York City, Madrid and Paris.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] London became the first city to host the modern Olympics three times, having previously hosted the Summer Games in 1908 and 1948.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Construction for the Games involved considerable redevelopment, with an emphasis on sustainability.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The main focus was a new 200-hectare (490-acre) Olympic Park, constructed on a former industrial site in Stratford, East London.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Games also used venues that already existed before the bid.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The United States topped the medal table, winning the most gold medals (48) and the highest number of medals overall (105).
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] China finished second with a total of 91 medals (38 gold) and Great Britain came third with 65 medals overall (29 gold).
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Michael Phelps of the United States became the most decorated Olympic athlete of all time, winning his 22nd medal.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Saudi Arabia, Qatar and Brunei entered female athletes for the first time, meaning that every currently eligible country has now sent a female competitor to at least one Olympic Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Women's boxing was included for the first time, and the 2012 Games became the first at which every sport had female competitors.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Games received considerable praise for their organisation, with the volunteers, the British military and public enthusiasm commended particularly highly.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Games were described as happy and glorious.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony, directed by the Academy Award winner Danny Boyle, received widespread acclaim.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] These were the final Olympic Games under the IOC presidency of Belgian Jacques Rogge, who was succeeded by German Thomas Bach the next year.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] London was chosen over Birmingham to represent Great Britain's bid by the British Olympic Association.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] By 15 July 2003—the deadline for interested cities to submit bids to the International Olympic Committee (IOC)—nine cities had submitted bids to host the 2012 Summer Olympics: Havana, Istanbul, Leipzig, London, Madrid, Moscow, New York City, Paris and Rio de Janeiro.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] On 18 May 2004, as a result of a scored technical evaluation, the IOC reduced the number of cities to five: London, Madrid, Moscow, New York and Paris.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] All five submitted their candidate files by 19 November 2004 and were visited by the IOC inspection team during February and March 2005.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Paris bid suffered two setbacks during the IOC inspection visit: a number of strikes and demonstrations coinciding with the visits, and a report that a key member of the bid team, Guy Drut, would face charges over alleged corrupt party political finances.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Throughout the process, Paris was widely seen as the favourite, particularly as this was its third bid in recent years.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] London was initially seen as lagging behind Paris by a considerable margin.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Its position began to improve after the appointment of Lord Coe as the new chair of the London Organising Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games (LOCOG) on 19 May 2004.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In late August 2004, reports predicted a tie between London and Paris.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] On 6 June 2005 the IOC released its evaluation reports for the five candidate cities.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] They did not contain any scores or rankings, but the report for Paris was considered the most positive.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] London was close behind, having closed most of the gap observed by the initial evaluation in 2004.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] New York and Madrid also received very positive evaluations.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] On 1 July 2005, when asked who would win, Jacques Rogge said, "I cannot predict it since I don't know how the IOC members will vote.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] But my gut feeling tells me that it will be very close.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] On 6 July 2005 the final selection was announced at the 117th IOC Session in Singapore.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Moscow was the first city to be eliminated, followed by New York and Madrid.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The final two contenders were London and Paris.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] At the end of the fourth round of voting, London won the right to host the 2012 Games with 54 votes to 50.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The celebrations in London were short-lived, being overshadowed by bombings on London's transport system less than 24 hours after the announcement.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Five years after the games, Paris would later be selected to host the 2024 Summer Olympics on 13 September 2017.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The London Organising Committee of the Olympic Games (LOCOG) was created to oversee the staging of the Games, and held its first board meeting on 3 October 2005.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The committee, chaired by Lord Coe, was in charge of implementing and staging the Games, while the Olympic Delivery Authority (ODA), established in April 2006, was in charge of construction of the venues and infrastructure.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Government Olympic Executive (GOE), a unit within the Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS), was the lead government body for coordinating the London 2012 Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] It focused on oversight of the Games, cross-programme management, and the London 2012 Olympic Legacy before and after the Games that would benefit London and the wider United Kingdom.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The organisation was also responsible for the supervision of the £9.3 billion of public sector funding.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In August 2011 security concerns arose surrounding the hosting of the Olympic Games in London, following the 2011 England riots.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Some countries expressed safety concerns, despite the IOC's assurance that the riots would not affect the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The IOC's Coordination Commission for the 2012 Games completed its tenth and final visit to London in March 2012.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Its members concluded that "London is ready to host the world this summer".
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Facilities of the 2012 Summer Olympics in the Greater London area.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games used a mixture of new venues, existing and historic facilities, and temporary facilities, some of them in well-known locations such as Hyde Park and Horse Guards Parade.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] After the Games, some of the new facilities would be reused in their Olympic form, while others were resized or relocated.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The majority of venues were divided into three zones within Greater London: the Olympic Zone, the River Zone and the Central Zone.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In addition there were a few venues that, by necessity, were outside the boundaries of Greater London, such as the Weymouth and Portland National Sailing Academy some 125 mi (201 km) southwest of London, which hosted the sailing events.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The football tournament was staged at several grounds around the UK.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Work began on the Park in December 2006, when a sports hall in Eton Manor was pulled down.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The athletes' village in Portland was completed in September 2011.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In November 2004 the 200-hectare (500-acre) Olympic Park plans were revealed.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The plans for the site were approved in September 2004 by Tower Hamlets, Newham, Hackney and Waltham Forest.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The redevelopment of the area to build the Olympic Park required compulsory purchase orders of property.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The London Development Agency was in dispute with London and Continental Railways about the orders in November 2005.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] By May 2006, 86% of the land had been bought as businesses fought eviction.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Residents who opposed the eviction tried to find ways to stop it by setting up campaigns, but they had to leave as 94% of land was bought and the other 6% bought as a £9 billion regeneration project started.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There were some issues with the original venues not being challenging enough or being financially unviable.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Both the Olympic road races and the mountain bike event were initially considered to be too easy, so they were eventually scheduled on new locations.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic marathon course, which was set to finish in the Olympic stadium, was moved to The Mall, since closing Tower Bridge was deemed to cause traffic problems in central London.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] North Greenwich Arena 2 was scrapped in a cost-cutting exercise, Wembley Arena being used for badminton and rhythmic gymnastics events instead.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Test events were held throughout 2011 and 2012, either through an existing championship such as 2012 Wimbledon Championships or as a specially created event held under the banner of *London Prepares*.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Team GB House was the British Olympic Association's operational HQ up to and during the 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Designed by architects Gebler Tooth on the top floor of an office building in Westfield Stratford City, it combined the team HQ, athletes' "Friends and Family" lounge, Press Centre, and VIP lounge.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] IOC's initial evaluation felt that, if transport improvements were delivered in time for the Games, London would cope.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Transport for London (TfL) carried out numerous improvements in preparation for 2012, including the expansion of the London Overground's East London Line, upgrades to the Docklands Light Railway and the North London Line, and the introduction of a new "Javelin" high-speed rail service.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] According to Network Rail, an additional 4,000 train services operated during the Games, and train operators ran longer trains during the day.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] During the Games, Stratford International station was not served by any international services (just as it had not been before the Games), westbound trains did not stop at Hackney Wick railway station, and Pudding Mill Lane DLR station closed entirely during the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] TfL also built a £25 million cable car across the River Thames, called the Emirates Air Line, to link 2012 Olympics venues.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] It was inaugurated in June 2012 and crosses the Thames between Greenwich Peninsula and the Royal Docks, carrying up to 2,500 passengers an hour, cutting journey times between The O2 and the ExCeL exhibition centre and providing a crossing every 30 seconds.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The plan was to have 80% of athletes travel less than 20 minutes to their event and 93% of them within 30 minutes of their event.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic Park would be served by ten separate railway lines with a combined capacity of 240,000 passengers per hour.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In addition, LOCOG planned for 90% of the venues to be served by three or more types of public transport.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Two park-and-ride sites off the M25 with a combined capacity of 12,000 cars were 25 minutes away from the Olympic Park.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Another park-and-ride site was planned in Ebbsfleet with a capacity for 9,000 cars where spectators could board a 10-minute shuttle train service.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] To get spectators to Eton Dorney, four park-and-ride schemes were set up.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] These Park and Ride services were operated by First Games Transport.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] TfL defined a network of roads leading between venues as the Olympic Route Network; roads connecting all of the Olympic venues located within London.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Many of these roads also contained special "Olympic lanes" marked with the Olympic rings—reserved for the use of Olympic athletes, officials, and other VIPs during the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Members of the public driving in an Olympic lane were subject to a fine of £130.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Additionally, London buses would not include roads with Olympic lanes on their routes.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Concerns were expressed at the logistics of spectators travelling to the events outside London.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In particular, the sailing events at Portland had no direct motorway connections, and local roads are heavily congested by tourist traffic in the summer.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] However, a £77 million relief road connecting Weymouth to Dorchester was built and opened in 2011.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Some £16 million was put aside for the rest of the improvements.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] TfL created a promotional campaign and website, *Get Ahead of the Games*, to help provide information related to transport during the Olympics and Paralympics.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Through the campaign, TfL also encouraged the use of cycling as a mode of transport.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] A temporary terminal was created at Heathrow Airport to be used by 10,100 departing athletes after the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Up to 35% more bags than normal were expected on 13 August, which was predicted to be the busiest day in the airport's history, according to Nick Cole, head of Olympic and Paralympic planning at Heathrow.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] A study from Oxford University found that the sports-related costs of London 2012 amounted to US$15 billion, compared with $4.6 billion for Rio 2016, $40–44 billion for Beijing 2008, and $51 billion for Sochi 2014 (the most expensive Olympics in history).
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] London 2012 went over budget by 76% in real terms, measured from bid to completion.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] This does not include wider costs for urban and transport infrastructure, which often equal or exceed the sports-related costs.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The costs of staging the Games were separate from those for building the venues and infrastructure and redeveloping the land for the Olympic Park.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] While the Games were privately funded, the venues and infrastructure were largely financed using public money.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] According to *The Wall Street Journal*, the original budget for the Games was increased to about £9.3 billion (US$15.28 billion) in 2007.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The revised figures were announced to the House of Commons on 15 March 2007 by Tessa Jowell.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Unpaid volunteers known as Games Makers performed a variety of tasks before and during the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] A target of 70,000 volunteers was set as early as 2004.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] When recruitment took place in 2010, more than 240,000 applications were received.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Sebastian Coe said in February 2012, "Our Games Makers will contribute a total of around eight million volunteer hours during the Games and the Games simply wouldn't happen without them".
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The volunteers wore clothing that included purple and red polo shirts and jackets, beige trousers, grey socks and grey-and-white trainers, which they collected from the Uniform Distribution and Accreditation Centre.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Volunteers also wore photo accreditation badges that were also worn by officials, athletes, family members and media, which gained them access to specific venues and buildings around the site.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Organisers estimated that some 8 million tickets would be available for the Olympic Games, and 1.5 million tickets for the Paralympic Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] LOCOG aimed to raise £375–£400 million in ticket sales.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There were also free events such as marathon, triathlon and road cycling, although, for the first time in Olympic history, the sailing events were ticketed.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Eventually, more than 7,000,000 tickets were sold.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Following IOC rules, people applied for tickets from the NOC of their country of residence.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] European Union residents were able to apply for tickets in any EU country.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In Great Britain, ticket prices ranged from £20 for many events to £2,012 for the most expensive seats at the opening ceremony.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Some free tickets were given to military personnel as part of the Tickets For Troops scheme, as well as to survivors and families of those who died during the 7 July 2005 London bombings.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Initially, people were able to apply for tickets via a website from 15 March until 26 April 2011.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There was a huge demand for tickets, with a demand of more than three times the number of tickets available.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] On 11 May 2012 a round of nearly one million "second chance" tickets went on sale over a 10-day period between 23 June and 3 July 2011.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] About 1.7 million tickets were available for football and 600,000 for other sports, including archery, field hockey, football, judo, boxing and volleyball.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Ten sports had sold out by 8 am of the first day.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] During the closing ceremony of the 2008 Olympics, the Olympic Flag was formally handed over from the Mayor of Beijing to the Mayor of London.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] This was followed by a section highlighting London, One month later, the Olympic and Paralympic flags were raised outside the London City Hall.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] A countdown clock in Trafalgar Square was unveiled, 500 days before the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] It was a two-sided clock with the Paralympic countdown on the other side.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The countdown to the start of the Olympics began with a ceremony for the lighting of the Olympic flame in Olympia, Greece.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The police led the security operation (named **Operation Olympics** by the Ministry of Defence), with 10,000 officers available, supported by 13,500 members of the British Armed Forces.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Naval and air assets were deployed as part of the security operation, including ships situated in the Thames, Typhoon fighter jets and surface-to-air missiles; it was the biggest security operation Britain had faced in decades.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The cost of security increased from £282 million to £553 million, and the figure of 13,500 armed forces personnel was greater than the number deployed at the time in Afghanistan.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Metropolitan Police and the Royal Marines carried out security exercises in preparation for the Olympics on 19 January 2012, with 50 marine police officers in rigid inflatables and fast response boats, joined by up to 100 military personnel and a Royal Navy Lynx helicopter.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Ministry of Defence distributed leaflets to residents of the Lexington building in Bow, announcing that a missile system was to be stationed on top of the water tower.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Ministry said it probably would use Starstreak missiles and that site evaluations had taken place, but that no final decision had taken place.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Approximately 4,700 Olympic and Paralympic medals were produced by the Royal Mint at Llantrisant.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] They were designed by David Watkins (Olympics) and Lin Cheung (Paralympics).
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] 99% of the gold, silver and copper was donated by Rio Tinto from a mine in Salt Lake County, Utah in the U.S.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The remaining 1% came from a Mongolian mine.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Each medal weighs 375–400 g (13.2–14.1 oz), has a diameter of 85 mm (3.3 in) and is 7 mm (0.28 in) thick, with the sport and discipline engraved on the rim.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The medals were transferred to the Tower of London vaults on 2 July 2012 for storage.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Each gold medal is 92.5 percent silver and 1.34 percent gold, with the remainder copper.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The silver medal is 92.5 percent silver, with the remainder copper.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The bronze medal is made up of 97 percent copper, 2.5 percent zinc, and 0.5 per cent tin.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The value of the materials in the gold medal was about £410 (US$644), the silver about £210 (US$330), and the bronze about £3 (US$4.71) as of 30 July 2012.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] For the first time in Olympic history, the same podium design was used for both the Summer Olympics and the Summer Paralympics, reflecting the organizers’ intention to establish a unified visual identity across the two events.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The royal purple podiums and ceremonial costumes used during the victory ceremonies of the 2012 Summer Olympics were designed by students from the Royal College of Art in collaboration with the London 2012 organizing committee.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The students worked on the project for approximately eight months, developing designs intended to reflect the identity and atmosphere of the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The podiums were inspired by the official emblem of the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The students used the angular design of the logo as the basis for the podium concept, extending its lines outward to create a three-dimensional structure intended to be viewed from multiple angles.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] To complement the visual identity adopted across the Olympic venues, the podiums were produced in a purple colour scheme, which organizers stated was intended to embody the energy and dynamism of the athletes competing at the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The podiums featured dynamic lines symbolizing the energy of both the Olympic Games and the athletes competing in them.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympics torch relay ran from 19 May to 27 July 2012, before the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Plans for the relay were developed in 2010–11, with the torch-bearer selection process announced on 18 May 2011.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The torch was designed by Edward Barber and Jay Osgerby.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] On 18 May 2012 the Olympic flame arrived at RNAS Culdrose in Cornwall from Greece on flight BA2012, operated by a British Airways Airbus A319 named "Firefly".
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The relay lasted 70 days, with 66 evening celebrations and six island visits, and involved some 8,000 people carrying the torch about 8,000 mi (12,875 km), starting from Land's End in Cornwall.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The torch had three days outside the United Kingdom when it visited the Isle of Man on 2 June, Dublin in Ireland, on 6 June, and both Guernsey and Jersey on 15 July.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The relay focused on National Heritage Sites, locations with sporting significance, key sporting events, schools registered with the Get Set School Network, green spaces and biodiversity, Live Sites (city locations with large screens), and festivals and other events.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Dumfries and Galloway was the only Region in the whole of the United Kingdom that had the Olympic Torch pass through it twice.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] A group of young athletes, nominated by retired Olympic athletes, ran the torch around the stadium.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] These torchbearers were Callum Airlie, Jordan Duckitt, Desiree Henry, Katie Kirk, Cameron MacRitchie, Aidan Reynolds and Adelle Tracey.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Together the torchbearers each lit a petal that spread the fire to the 204 petals of the cauldron, representing the countries that participated in the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The cauldron was designed by Thomas Heatherwick.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic Park was planned to incorporate 45 hectares of wildlife habitat, with a total of 525 bird boxes and 150 bat boxes.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Local waterways and riverbanks were enhanced as part of the process.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Renewable energy also featured at the Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] It was originally planned to provide 20% of the energy for the Olympic Park and Village from renewable technologies; however, only 9% of it was achieved.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Proposals to meet the original target included large-scale on-site wind turbines and hydroelectric generators in the River Thames, but these plans were scrapped for safety reasons.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The focus subsequently moved to installing solar panels on some buildings, and providing the opportunity to recover energy from waste.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Where it could not be reused or recycled, food packaging for use at the Olympics—including fast-food wrappers, sandwich boxes and drink cartons—was made from compostable materials like starch and cellulose-based bioplastics.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] After use, many of these materials were suitable for anaerobic digestion (AD), allowing them to be made into renewable energy.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Post-Games, buildings like the Water Polo Arena were relocated elsewhere.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Building parts like roofing covers and membranes of different temporary venues were recycled via VinyLoop.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] This allowed organisers to meet the standards of the Olympic Delivery Authority concerning environmental protection.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] London 2012 inaugurated Olympic Games guidelines that included the recycling of PVC, which was used for temporary buildings such as the Basketball Arena and for the temporary parts of permanent venues such as the Olympic Stadium.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In the Water Polo Arena, PVC roofing was made from recycled cushions to provide insulation.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Basically, PVC stretched over lightweight steel frame.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] This design solution makes them efficient to install, reduces the need for any significant foundations and are, of course, reusable.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] We were challenged by the public around the use of PVC; but we considered it to be the right material for certain functions.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Cultural Olympiad comprised many programmes, with more than 500 events spread over four years across the whole of the United Kingdom, and culminating in the London 2012 Festival.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Titled "The Isles of Wonder", the opening ceremony began at 21:00 British Summer Time (UTC+1) on 27 July in the Olympic Stadium.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Academy Award–winning director Danny Boyle was artistic director and Rick Smith of Underworld was musical director.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony was immediately seen as a tremendous success, widely praised as a "masterpiece" and "a love letter to Britain".
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The principal sections of the artistic display represented Britain's Industrial Revolution, National Health Service, literary heritage, popular music and culture, and were noted for their vibrant storytelling and use of music.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The Games were officially opened by Queen Elizabeth II, accompanied by Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] This was the second Olympic Games opened personally by the Queen, the first being in 1976 in Montreal, Canada.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The ceremony featured a short comic film starring Daniel Craig as the secret agent James Bond and the Queen as herself.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There was also a musical comedy item starring Rowan Atkinson as Mr.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Bean playing along with the London Symphony Orchestra.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] These were widely ascribed to Britain's sense of humour.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Live musical performers included Frank Turner, Dame Evelyn Glennie, Mike Oldfield, Dizzee Rascal, Arctic Monkeys and Sir Paul McCartney who performed "Hey Jude" as the closing act.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Broadcast live on BBC One, the ceremony attracted a peak viewing audience of over 27 million in the UK.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The closing ceremony was held on 12 August.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] It featured a flashback fiesta to British music with the Who closing the performance.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The ceremony also included a handover of the Olympic flag by Boris Johnson, Mayor of London, to Eduardo Paes, Mayor of Rio de Janeiro, the host city of the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In his closing address, Jacques Rogge described the Games as "happy and glorious".
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] During the Games, some countries and continents had a "national house".
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] These temporary meeting places for supporters, athletes and other followers were located throughout London.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The 2012 Summer Olympics featured 26 different sports encompassing 40 disciplines and 302 medal events.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Women's boxing was included in the programme for the first time, and 36 women competed in three weight classes.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There was a special dispensation for the shooting events, which would otherwise have been illegal under UK gun law.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] In tennis, mixed doubles returned to the Olympic programme for the first time since 1924.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] London's bid featured the same 28 sports that had been included in other recent Summer Olympics, but the IOC voted to drop baseball and softball from the 2012 Games just two days after London had been selected as the host city.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There was an appeal, but the IOC voted to uphold the decision, and the two sports were scheduled to be discontinued after their last appearance at the 2008 Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The IOC then voted on whether to replace them; karate, squash, golf, roller sports and rugby sevens were considered.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Karate and squash were the two final nominees, but neither received enough votes to reach the required two-thirds majority.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Although formal demonstration sports were eliminated after the 1992 Summer Olympics, special tournaments for non-Olympic sports can be run during the Games, such as the Wushu tournament at the 2008 Summer Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] There were attempts to run Twenty20 cricket and netball tournaments alongside the 2012 Games, but neither campaign was successful.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The final official schedule was released on 15 February 2011.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] These Olympic Games resulted in 32 world records in eight sports.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The largest number of records were set in swimming, at eight.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] China, Great Britain and the United States set the most records, with five each.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 85 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) won medals, 54 of those countries winning at least one gold medal.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] Seven NOCs won their first ever Olympic medal: Bahrain (gold), Botswana (silver), Cyprus (silver), Gabon (silver), Grenada (gold), Guatemala (silver), and Montenegro (silver).
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p01] The United States finished at the top of the table, winning 48 gold medals and a total of 104 medals.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The host broadcaster was Olympic Broadcasting Services (OBS), an agency of the IOC.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The OBS used its own cameras and crews subcontracted from other Olympic broadcasters to cover the events.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The base video and audio were sold to other broadcasters, who added their own commentary and presentation.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The official recording format of the 2012 Summer Olympics used Panasonic's digital technologies.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The official video was produced and distributed from the International Broadcast Centre in 1080/50i High-Definition (HD) format.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Panasonic announced that DVCPRO HD would be the official recording format.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] OBS London used P2 HD shoulder-mount camcorders.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The IOC wanted television coverage to reach as broad a worldwide audience as possible, and several national and regional broadcasters covered London 2012.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] In the UK, the BBC carried the Olympics and Channel 4 the Paralympics.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The BBC aimed to broadcast all 5,000 hours of the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] BBC Parliament's Freeview channel was suspended, BBC Three's on-air time was extended so that it could show Olympic events in the daytime, and 24 additional BBC Olympics channels were available via cable, satellite and the internet in the UK.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The US television rights, owned by NBC, accounted for more than half the rights revenue for the IOC.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Despite high viewership, many viewers were disappointed with NBC's coverage.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The operations of broadcasters granted rights to the Games were hosted in the dedicated International Broadcast Centre inside the security cordon of the Olympic Park.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] YouTube planned to stream the Games in 64 territories in Asia and Sub-Saharan Africa where there were no official broadcasters.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] In Sri Lanka a dispute occurred between Sri Lanka Rupavahini Corporation (SLRC) and MBC Networks (MTV/MBC) as to who was the official broadcaster of the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] This problem was caused as Asia-Pacific Broadcasting Union (ABU) had offered the official broadcasting rights to both networks, as both of the networks were ABU members.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] So SLRC filed a case against MBC Networks for broadcasting rights at the Colombo Magistrate's Court.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Considering the case, the court issued a special court order preventing MBC Networks' Olympic broadcast and stated that SLRC should be the sole broadcaster.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] However, when the Games started, both networks broadcast most of the events simultaneously.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Another dispute had previously occurred between Carlton Sports Network (CSN) and SLRC, but the Sports Minister, Mahindananda Aluthgamage, had stated that SLRC had the exclusive rights.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] In November 2012 the IOC announced the winners of the Golden Ring Awards for the best broadcast coverage of the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Best Olympic Sports Production was awarded to the sailing, produced by Christopher Lincoln, Gary Milkis, and Ursula Romero.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The production for the canoe/kayak slalom and the rowing/canoe sprint came second and third respectively.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The award for Best On Air Promotion went to NBC with Foxtel and ZDF finishing second and third.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] NBC Olympics also won the Best Olympic Feature category, as Sky Italia came second and ZDF third.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The Best Athlete Profile award went to TV Record's profile of Sarah Menezes, NBC came second with their profile of David Rudisha, and ESPN Latin America took third place with a profile of Miguel Correa and Ruben Rezola.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The award for Best Olympic Programme went to NBC, host broadcasters the BBC took second place for Super Saturday (the middle Saturday of the Games), and third place was claimed by the Nine Network for their live coverage of Day 16 of the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] "Survival" by Muse was announced as the official song of the Olympics, to be played by international broadcasters reporting on the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The track was noted to express a sense of conviction and determination to win.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] In August 2009 Royal Mail commissioned artists and illustrators to design 30 stamps, which were released in batches of 10 between 2009 and 2011.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The last ones were released on 22 July 2011.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Two £5 coins designed by Saiman Miah were made to commemorate the Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] As with other Olympics since 1952, the Royal Mint struck a set of commemorative one-kilogram gold and silver coins.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The official motto for the 2012 Summer Olympics was "Inspire a generation".
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] It was chosen to highlight the organisers' commitment to inspire the world, including younger generations, to get involved in sporting events through the Games' legacy.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] A secondary motto of "Be part of it" was also used throughout marketing.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] There were two London 2012 logos: one used for the bidding process, and the other used in the branding for the Games themselves.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The bid logo, created by Kino Design, was a ribbon with blue, yellow, black, green, and red stripes winding through the text "LONDON 2012", making the shape of the River Thames in East London.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The main logo, designed by Wolff Olins and published on 4 June 2007, is a representation of the number 2012, with the Olympic Rings embedded within the zero.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Public reaction to the main logo in a June 2007 BBC poll was negative; more than 80% of votes gave it the lowest possible rating.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Several newspapers ran their own logo competitions, displaying alternative submissions from their readers, and several writers from news agencies criticised the logo.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] It was suggested that the logo resembled the American cartoon characters Lisa Simpson and Bart Simpson performing fellatio.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] In February 2011 Iran threatened to boycott the Olympics, complaining that the logo appeared to spell out the word "Zion".
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The four main colours used in the branding of the Games were pink, blue, green and orange.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] These colours were chosen to showcase the spirit of the Games: energetic, spirited, youthful, and bright.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The auxiliary colours used in the branding were dark purple, grey, and gold.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] These were mostly used in symbols and graphics to offset the brightness of the main colours.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The official mascots for the 2012 Summer Olympics and Paralympic Games were unveiled on 19 May 2010.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Wenlock and Mandeville are animations depicting two drops of steel from a steelworks in Bolton.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] They are named after Much Wenlock, a town in Shropshire that holds a forerunner of the current Olympic Games, and Stoke Mandeville, a village in Buckinghamshire where a forerunner of the Paralympic Games was first held.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The writer Michael Morpurgo wrote the story concept for the mascots, and an animation was produced.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Four stories have been created about the mascots: *Out Of A Rainbow*, *Adventures On A Rainbow*, *Rainbow Rescue*, and *Rainbow to the Games*.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The 1981 Academy Award for Best Picture–winning film *Chariots of Fire*, which tells the story of two British athletes in the 1924 Olympics, was a recurring theme in promotions for the 2012 Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] A digitally re-mastered version of *Chariots of Fire* was released on 13 July 2012 and screened in over 100 UK cinemas as part of the celebrations, and a stage adaptation ran in London theatres from 9 May 2012 to 5 January 2013.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The film's theme tune was performed during the opening ceremony by the London Symphony Orchestra, conducted by Simon Rattle.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The performance was accompanied by a comedic skit by Rowan Atkinson, which included the opening beach-running footage from the film.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] A new orchestration of the film's theme tune was played during each medal presentation of the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] During the lead-up to the Games, there were controversies over sponsorship, the athletes' use of social media, and several political issues.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] After a complicated lottery process, thousands of people failed to secure seats for the events they wanted, but a large number of empty seats were observed early in the Games, even at some of the most popular events.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] There was speculation that this was due to a failure of corporate sponsors to make use of tickets they had received.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] During the Games, eight competitors in the badminton women's doubles were disqualified for "not using best efforts", when they tried to lose matches in the group stage to obtain more favourable fixtures in the knockout rounds.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] A number of results in boxing, gymnastics and judo were overturned by officials after initial decisions were appealed against.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] It was announced before the Summer Games that half of all the competitors would be tested for drugs, with 150 scientists set to take 6,000 samples between the start of the Games and the end of the Paralympic Games.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Every competitor who won a medal was also tested.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympic laboratory tested up to 400 samples every day for more than 240 prohibited substances.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Although there were less than 10 doping violations detected during the games, in the years following many samples were retested with improved laboratory procedures.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] This resulted in a large number of disqualifications and rescinded medals.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] As of mid 2024, 44 medals have been stripped due to doping violations with around 130 total disqualifications.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] In particular, almost 50 were from Russian athletes.
[src:alkmaar/2012-summer-olympics-p02] Testing for drugs was completed by GSK (GlaxoSmithKline).
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Rio de Janeiro was announced as the host city at the 121st IOC Session in Copenhagen, Denmark, on 2 October 2009.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] 11,238 athletes from 207 nations took part in the 2016 Games, including first-time entrants Kosovo, South Sudan, and the Refugee Olympic Team.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] With 306 sets of medals, the Games featured 28 Olympic sports, including rugby sevens and golf, which were added to the Olympic program in 2009.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] These sporting events took place at 33 venues in the host city and at five separate venues in the Brazilian cities of São Paulo, Belo Horizonte, Salvador, Brasília, and Manaus.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] These were also the first Summer Olympics to take place under the International Olympic Committee (IOC) presidency of Thomas Bach.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The games were opened by acting president of Brazil (and later president), Michel Temer and closed by Bach.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The United States topped the medal table, winning the most gold medals (46) and the highest number of medals overall (121); the U.S. team also won its 1,000th Summer Olympic gold medal.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Great Britain finished second and the only country to increase its tally of medals in the Summer Olympiad immediately after being the host nation.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Host nation Brazil won seven gold medals and 19 total medals, its best result at any Olympics, finishing in thirteenth place.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Bahrain, Fiji, Ivory Coast, Jordan, Kosovo, Puerto Rico, Singapore, Tajikistan, and Vietnam all won their first gold medals, as did the group of Independent Olympic Athletes (from Kuwait).
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The bidding process for the 2016 Summer Olympics was officially launched on 16 May 2007.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The first step for each city was to submit an initial application to the International Olympic Committee by 13 September 2007, confirming their intention to bid.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Completed official bid files containing answers to a 25-question IOC form were to be submitted by each city by the deadline of 14 January 2008.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] On 4 June 2008, two months before the Beijing Olympics, four candidate cities were chosen for the shortlist: Chicago, Madrid, Rio de Janeiro, and Tokyo, which had already hosted the Summer Olympics in 1964.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Three cities—Baku, Doha, and Prague—failed to reach the candidature phase.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Nawal El Moutawakel of Morocco headed the 10-member Evaluation Commission, having also chaired the evaluation commission for the 2012 Summer Olympics bids, which was awarded to London, United Kingdom.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The commission made on-site inspections in the second quarter of 2009.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] They issued a comprehensive technical appraisal for IOC members on 2 September, one month before the elections.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Many safeguards were put in place to prevent bidding cities from communicating with or directly influencing the 115 IOC members eligible to vote in the elections.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] For example, cities could not invite any IOC member to visit, nor could they send anything that could be construed as a gift.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Nonetheless, bidding cities invested large sums in their PR and media programs to indirectly influence the IOC members by garnering domestic support and backing from sports media and general international media.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The final voting was held in Copenhagen on 2 October 2009, with Madrid and Rio de Janeiro considered favorites to secure the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Chicago was eliminated after the first round of voting, and Tokyo after the second (The latter city would eventually be awarded the 2020 Summer Olympics in 2013).
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Rio de Janeiro took a significant lead over Madrid, heading into the final round; the lead was held, and Rio de Janeiro was announced as host of the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] On 26 June 2011, it was reported on Around The Rings that Roderlei Generali, the COO of the Rio de Janeiro Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games, resigned just one year after taking the job at ROOC.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] This came just five months after CCO Flávio Pestana quit for personal reasons.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Pestana withdrew later during the 2012 Summer Paralympics, and Renato Ciuchin was then appointed as COO.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Events took place at eighteen existing venues, nine new venues constructed specifically for the Games, and seven temporary venues.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] For the events held in Rio de Janeiro, each event was held in one of four geographically segregated Olympic clusters–Barra, Copacabana, Deodoro, and Maracanã–as was done for the 2007 Pan American Games.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Several of the venues were located at the Barra Cluster Olympic Park.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Nearly half of the athletes could reach their venues in less than 10 minutes, and almost 75 per cent could do so in less than 25 minutes.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Of the 34 competition venues, eight underwent some permanent works, seven were totally temporary and nine were constructed as permanent legacy venues.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The largest venue at the Games in terms of seating capacity was the 75,000-seat Maracanã Stadium, which served as the ceremonies venue and site of the football finals.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The second largest stadium was the 60,000-seat Estádio Olímpico Nilton Santos (formerly João Havelange during the Games), which hosted track and field events.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The athletes' village was said to be the largest in Olympic history.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The Barra Olympic Park is a cluster of nine sporting venues in Barra da Tijuca, in the west zone of Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The site was formerly occupied by the Autódromo Internacional Nelson Piquet, also known as the Jacarepaguá Formula One circuit.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] As well as the Estádio Olímpico João Havelange and Maracanã and in Rio de Janeiro, football matches took place at five venues in the cities of São Paulo, Belo Horizonte, and the more distant Salvador, Brasília and Manaus.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Rio's historical downtown underwent an urban waterfront revitalization project known as *Porto Maravilha*, covering 5 km2 (1.9 mi2) in area.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The project aimed to redevelop the port area, increase the city center's attractiveness, and enhance Rio's competitive position in the global economy.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The urban renovation involved 700 km (430 mi) of public networks for water supply, sanitation, drainage, electricity, gas and telecom; 4 km (2.5 mi) of tunnels; 70 km (43 mi) of roads; 650 km2 (250 mi2) of sidewalks; 17 km (11 mi) of bike path; 15,000 trees; and three sanitation treatment plants.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] As part of this renovation, a new tram was built from the Santos Dumont Airport to Rodoviária Novo Rio, due to open in April 2016.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The Games required over 200 kilometers of security fencing.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] A 15,000 square meter warehouse in Barra da Tijuca was used to assemble and supply the furniture and fittings for the Olympic Village.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The second warehouse of 90,000 square meters in Duque de Caxias, near the roads that provide access to the venues, contained all the equipment needed for the sporting events.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The medals were produced by the Casa da Moeda do Brasil (the Brazilian National Mint).
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The medal design was unveiled on 15 June 2016.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] They were designed to be environmentally friendly using recycled materials; the bronze and silver medals contained 30% recycled materials.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The gold medals were produced using gold that had been mined and extracted according to a set of sustainability criteria, such as being extracted without the use of mercury.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The medals feature a wreath design on the front, and in keeping with tradition, the obverse features Nike, the Greek goddess of victory.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] A wooden carrying box accompanied each medal.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Medalists were also awarded a trophy in the shape of the Games' emblem.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] In May 2017, an Associated Press article disclosed that over 100 athletes who had won medals at the Rio Olympics reported that their medals were showing some damage, including black spots, flaking, or surface degrading.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Rio officials offered to replace any defective medals and found problems with 6 to 7 percent of all those awarded.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The Rio 2016 podiums featured designs and vegetation reminiscent of the city of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The podiums were made from wood and adorned with foliage in keeping with the natural “Look” of the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] They also needed to be light enough to be easily carried and assembled, but also strong enough to support up to 18 athletes on each stand.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The blue, green, yellow and orange colours that feature on the podium were symbolic of the Games' visual identity, inspired by Brazil’s harmonic diversity.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] All materials were organic and celebrated the tropical nature of Brazil, with the intent to be reused as furniture after the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] After the games, the podium from the Brazilian national football team's Olympic gold medal, that was 12 meters wide, was being auctioned off.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] It was divided into five parts, with values ranging from R$ 505,00 to R$ 925,00.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] In the end, it was businessman Sérgio Santos who ended up buying the piece.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic flame was lit on 21 April 2016 at the Temple of Hera in Olympia, the traditional start of the Greek phase of the torch relay.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The flame was handed over to the Brazilian organisers in a ceremony at the Panathenaic Stadium in Athens on 27 April.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] A brief stop-off was made in Switzerland to visit the IOC headquarters and the Olympic Museum in Lausanne, as well as the United Nations Office at Geneva.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The torch relay began its journey around Brazil on 3 May at the capital Brasília.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The flame visited more than 300 Brazilian cities, including all 26 state capitals and the Brazilian Federal District.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The relay ended in Rio de Janeiro on 5 August when the flame was used to light the Olympic cauldron during the opening ceremony.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Unpaid volunteers performed a variety of tasks before and during the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] A target of 50,000 volunteers was set as early as 2012.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] More than 240,000 applications were received when recruitment took place in 2014.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The clothing worn by the volunteers included yellow polo shirts and jackets, beige trousers, white socks, and green trainers, which they collected from the Uniform Distribution and Accreditation Centre.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Volunteers also wore photo accreditation badges which were allocated to officials, athletes, family members, and media, allowing them to gain access to specific venues and buildings around the site.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Many volunteers gave up their roles due to long working hours and insufficient free meals.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The ticket prices were announced on 16 September 2014, all of which were sold in Brazilian reais (BRL).
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 7.5 million tickets were to be sold in total, with ticket prices ranging from BRL 40 for many events to BRL 4,600 for the most expensive seats at the opening ceremony.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] About 3.8 million of these tickets were available for BRL 70 or less.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] As an aspect of its bid, Rio's organizing committee planned to focus on sustainability and environmental protection as a theme of the 2016 Games, going on to dub them a "Green Games for a Blue Planet".
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] However, some of these projects met with delays or faced economic shortfalls, leading some critics to believe that Rio would not be able to accomplish them.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The focus on environmental protection also influenced the implementation of certain Olympic protocols.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] To reduce emissions, the Olympic cauldron was designed to be smaller than previous iterations, using a kinetic sculpture to enhance its appearance in place of a larger body of flames.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The bronze and silver medals, as well as the ribbons on all medals, were designed to incorporate recycled materials.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The athletes were not presented with flowers during the medal ceremonies, as had been the tradition at previous Olympics (although floral displays were still used as part of the staging of medal presentations).
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The organizers considered the practice to be wasteful because the flowers were often thrown away and "would struggle to survive in the tropical Brazilian climate" if kept.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The podiums were designed using materials that could be recycled to make furniture.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The Future Arena, the venue for the handball competitions, was designed as a temporary modular structure whose components could be reconstructed after the Games to build schools.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] However, as of November 2017, the arena was still standing due to lack of funds to dismantle it and no allocation of funds to do so in the 2018 budget.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Portions of the opening ceremony were dedicated to the issue of climate change.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony took place at Maracanã Stadium on 5 August 2016, directed by Fernando Meirelles, Daniela Thomas, and Andrucha Waddington.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The ceremony highlighted aspects of Brazilian history and culture, and featured a segment narrated by Fernanda Montenegro and Judi Dench with an appeal to environmental conservation and the prevention of global warming.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The crowd in the stadium numbered 60,000 and the event was broadcast to an estimated global audience of three billion.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The ceremony included the inaugural presentation of the Olympic Laurel, an honor bestowed by the IOC on those that have made "significant achievements in education, culture, development and peace through sport"; the trophy was awarded to Kenyan athlete Kipchoge Keino.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The Games were officially opened by the acting president of Brazil, Michel Temer.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic cauldron was lit by long-distance runner Vanderlei Cordeiro de Lima, the men's marathon bronze medalist at the 2004 Olympics, who had also received the IOC's Pierre de Coubertin medal for sportsmanship after being attacked by a spectator and losing his lead in the race.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The cauldron was originally expected to be lit by Brazilian footballer Pelé, but he declined to participate due to health problems.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Following the opening ceremony, a public cauldron was lit in front of the Candelária Church by Jorge Gomes, a 14-year-old Brazilian athlete who had escaped from poverty to train as a runner.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The 2016 Summer Olympic program featured 28 sports encompassing 306 medal events.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The number of events in each of 42 discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] In April 2008, the IOC began accepting applications for two new sports to be introduced to the Olympic programme.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Baseball and softball (which were both dropped in 2005), karate, squash, golf, roller sports, and rugby union all applied to be included on the programme.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Formal presentations were made to the IOC executive board in June 2009.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] In August, the executive board initially gave its approval to rugby sevens—a seven-player version of rugby union—by a majority vote; baseball/softball, roller sports, and squash were removed from contention, leaving golf, karate, and rugby sevens in the running.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] A final vote was held on 9 October 2009, the closing day of the 121st IOC Session.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] At this session, a new voting system was in place: a sport now needed only a simple majority from the full IOC committee for approval rather than the two-thirds majority previously required.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The 121st IOC Session decided to add rugby sevens and golf to the Rio 2016 Olympic programme.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The tally for rugby was 81 in favor, with eight against, and golf was approved by 63 votes to 26.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Neither of these two sports was new to the Summer Olympics; rugby last featured in 1924, and golf in 1904.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] In May 2012, the International Sailing Federation announced that windsurfing would be replaced by kitesurfing at the 2016 Olympics, but this decision was reversed in November.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Twenty-seven world records and ninety-one Olympic records were set during the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The records were set in archery, athletics, canoeing, cycling track, modern pentathlon, rowing, shooting, swimming, and weightlifting.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] A number of events, most notably in aquatics, beach volleyball and track and field, were scheduled with sessions and matches occurring as late as 10:00 p.m. to midnight BRT.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] As Brasília time is only one hour ahead of the U.S.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Eastern Time Zone, certain marquee events were scheduled to occur during U.S. primetime hours (traditionally 8:00 to 11:00 p.m.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] ET, 9:00 p.m. to midnight BRT), allowing them to be broadcast live on the east coast as opposed to being delayed.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] This practice was also beneficial to Globo; a Brazilian critic noted that the network very rarely preempts its primetime telenovelas, as they are among the highest-rated programs in the country.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The closing ceremony of the 2016 Summer Olympics was held on 21 August 2016 from 20:00 to 22:50 BRT at the Maracanã Stadium.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The creative director for the ceremony was Rosa Magalhães.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Amid heavy rainfall, the ceremony began with interpretive dancers representing various landmarks in the host city.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Martinho da Vila then performed a rendition of "Carinhoso" by Pixinguinha.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] In another segment, introducing the athletes, singer Roberta Sá channeled Carmen Miranda, the fruit-headdress-wearing, mid-century Hollywood diva who endures as a beloved camp figure.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The Parade of Flags followed shortly after a choir of 27 children, representing the states of Brazil, sang the Brazilian national anthem.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The Oxford Olympics Study 2016 estimated the out-turn cost of the Rio 2016 Summer Olympics at US$4.6 billion in 2015-dollars.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Indirect capital costs were not included, such as for road, rail, or airport infrastructure, for hotel upgrades, or other business investment incurred in preparation for the Games but not directly related to staging the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The Rio Olympics' cost of US$4.6 billion compares with costs of US$40–44 billion for Beijing 2008 and US$51 billion for Sochi 2014, the two most expensive Olympics in history.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The average cost of the Summer Games since 1960 is US$5.2 billion.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] All 205 National Olympic Committees qualified at least one athlete.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The first three nations to qualify athletes for the Games were Germany, Great Britain, and the Netherlands, who each qualified four athletes for the team dressage by winning medals in the team event at the 2014 FEI World Equestrian Games.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] As host nation, Brazil received automatic entry for some sports including in all cycling disciplines and six places for weightlifting events.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The 2016 Summer Olympics were the first Games in which Kosovo and South Sudan were eligible to participate.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Bulgarian and Russian weightlifters were banned from Rio Olympics for numerous anti-doping violations.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Kuwait was banned in October 2015 for the second time in five years over government interference in the country's Olympic committee.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Kuwaiti athletes instead participated as "Independent Olympic Athletes".
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Due to the European migrant crisis and other reasons, the IOC allowed athletes to compete as Independent Olympians under the Olympic Flag.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] During the previous Summer Olympic Games, refugees were ineligible to compete because of their inability to represent their home NOCs.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] On 2 March 2016, the IOC finalized plans for a specific Refugee Olympic Team (ROT); out of 43 refugee athletes deemed potentially eligible, 10 were chosen to form the team.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Due to the suspension of the National Olympic Committee of Kuwait, participants from Kuwait were allowed to participate under the Olympic Flag as Independent Olympic Athletes.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] In November 2015, Russia was provisionally suspended from all international track and field athletic competitions by the International Association of Athletics Federations (IAAF) following a World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) report into a doping program in the country.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The IAAF announced that it would allow individual Russian athletes to apply for "exceptional eligibility" to participate in the Games as "neutral" athletes if it was independently verified that they had not engaged in doping nor in the Russian doping program.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] On 24 July 2016, the IOC rejected the IAAF and WADA's recommendations to allow athletes to compete neutrally, stating that the Olympic Charter "does not foresee such 'neutral athletes'" and that it was each country's National Olympic Committee decision on which athletes would be competing.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] As a result, Russian athletes competed under the Russian flag, although they would compete under a neutral flag in the 2018 Winter Olympics following several developments concerning the doping investigation.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] During the Games, some countries and continents had a national house.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] These temporary meeting places for supporters, athletes and other followers were located throughout Rio de Janeiro.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] This is currently based on the schedule released on the same day as ticket sales began, 31 March 2015.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The top ten listed NOCs by the number of gold medals are listed below.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Host nation Brazil finished in 13th place with a total of 19 medals (7 gold, 6 silver, and 6 bronze).
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Olympic Broadcasting Services served as the host broadcaster for the 2016 Games.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Produced from a total of seven mobile units, OBS distributed 40,000 hours of television footage and 60,000 hours of digital footage of the Games to its international rightsholders.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] For the first time in Olympic history, digital-oriented footage exceeded the amount of television-oriented footage.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The International Broadcast Centre was constructed in the Barra da Tijuca cluster.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] NHK and OBS once again filmed portions of the Games, including the opening ceremony and selected events, in 8K resolution video.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Additionally, expanding upon a 180-degree trial at the 2016 Winter Youth Olympics, 85 hours of video content were originated in 360-degree virtual reality formats.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] In the United States, NBCUniversal offered 4K content downconverted from the 8K footage and with HDR and Dolby Atmos support, to participating television providers.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Owing to their expertise in domestic broadcasts of the new sports introduced in Rio, NBCU and Sky New Zealand staff handled the production of the golf and rugby sevens events on behalf of OBS.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] In August 2009, the IOC reached a deal to sell domestic broadcast rights for the 2016 Summer Olympics to Grupo Globo.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Replacing Record, the deal covers free-to-air coverage on Rede Globo, pay TV, and digital rights to the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] In turn, Globo sublicensed partial free-to-air rights to Record, along with Band.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] IOC board member Richard Carrión described the agreement as "unprecedented", touting that "by working with Brazil's leading media organizations, we are confident that this represents a great deal for Olympic fans in the region.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] In November 2017, the International Olympic Committee announced the winners of the Golden rings in six categories for the best broadcast coverage of the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The Best Olympic Sports Production was awarded to Beach Volleyball, produced by Geoff Johnson and directed by Greg Breakell and Gary Milkis.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The production for the cycling road race and Sailing came second and third.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The next category was the best Olympic feature, for which TV Globo's show *Esporte Espetacular* finished third, and CCTV China's feature *A Sequel of Love* came second.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The winner was NBC Olympics for their feature *The Most Beautiful Thing*.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The third category was The Best Athlete Profile, for which RTBF from Belgium collected the third place prize for their profile of Nafi Thiam.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Globo went one better than the previous category coming second with their profile of Isaquias Queiroz.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The winner of the category again was NBC, this time for their piece on Wayde van Niekerk.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The Best On-Air Promotion was announced next, with the BBC Sport winning with NBC coming second this time and BNT from Bulgaria finishing third.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The Best Olympic Digital Service went to NBC, with ZDF and SporTV/Globosat picking up the second and third places.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The Best Olympic Programme was awarded to SporTV/Globosat, while TV Globo and BBC Sport completed the podium.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] On 24 November 2014, the official mascots of the 2016 Summer Olympics and Paralympics were unveiled, created by São Paulo-based animation company Birdo.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic mascot Vinicius, named after musician Vinicius de Moraes, represents Brazilian wildlife and carries design traits of cats, monkeys, and birds.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] According to their fictional backgrounds, the mascots "were both born from the joy of Brazilians after it was announced that Rio would host the Games".
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Brand director Beth Lula stated that the mascots were intended to reflect the diversity of Brazil's culture and people.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The names of the mascots were determined by a public vote whose results were announced on 14 December 2014.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The names, which reference the co-writers of the song "The Girl from Ipanema", won over two other sets of names, tallying 44 percent of 323,327 votes.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] At the Olympic wrestling events, coaches were given plush dolls of Vinicius to throw into the ring when they wished to challenge a referee's call.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The official emblem for the 2016 Summer Olympics was designed by Brazilian agency Tatíl Design and was unveiled on 31 December 2010, winning in a competition against 139 agencies.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The emblem represents three figures joined at their arms and feet, with the overall shape reflecting that of Sugarloaf Mountain.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] It was also designed to have a three-dimensional form, which designer Fred Gelli claimed made it the first 3D logo in the history of the Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] The logo has been noted as evoking Henri Matisse's painting *Dance*.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] There were also allegations by the Colorado-based Telluride Foundation that the logo had been plagiarized from its own; while also consisting of several figures linked in motion, the Telluride Foundation logo contains four figures.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] This was not the first time that the foundation had alleged plagiarism of its logo by a Brazilian event; in 2004, the linked figures element had been copied for the logo of Carnival celebrations in Salvador.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Gelli defended the allegations, stating that the concept of figures linked in embrace was not inherently original, as it was "an ancient reference" and "in the collective unconscious".
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p01] Gelli cited *Dance* as an influence of the logo's concept and stated that the designers had intentionally aimed to make the interpretation of the concept as dissimilar to others as possible.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] However, the Zika virus was not contracted by anyone competing in or attending the Olympics, and the Games went ahead normally with no major incident.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] There is no legally legitimate evidence of impropriety in the choice of Rio to host the Olympic games, at least as far as the Brazilian Olympic Committee or the politicians involved in the process are concerned.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] However, the specialized media raised suspicions about it.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] In 2014, Operation Car Wash, an investigation by the Federal Police of Brazil, uncovered unprecedented money laundering and corruption at the state-controlled oil company Petrobras.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] In early 2015, a series of protests against alleged corruption by the government of President Dilma Rousseff began in Brazil, triggered by revelations that numerous politicians were involved in the Petrobras affair.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] By early 2016, the scandal had escalated into a full-blown political crisis affecting not only President Rousseff, but also former President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, resulting in widespread demonstrations involving millions of protesters, both anti- and pro-Rousseff.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] At the same time, Brazil faced its worst economic recession since the 1990s, raising questions about whether the country was adequately prepared to host the Olympic Games against a volatile political and economic backdrop.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] On 12 May 2016, President Rousseff was stripped of her powers and duties for 180 days after an impeachment vote in the Federal Senate, with Vice President Michel Temer standing in as acting president during the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] On 5 October 2017, Brazilian Olympic Committee head Carlos Nuzman was arrested amid a money-laundering investigation into a $2 million payment that was allegedly made to secure votes for the bid to bring the Olympics to Rio.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] The money was believed to have been paid to former IAAF president Lamine Diack and his son Papa Massata Diack, who was a member of the IOC at the time of the alleged payment, which was three days before the vote in 2009.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] All three were charged with money laundering, along with the former Rio state governor Sérgio Cabral Filho (who was already in prison for money laundering offenses at the time), Brazilian businessman Arthur Soares, and ex-Brazilian Olympic Committee chief Leonardo Gryner.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] All six were charged with running a criminal organization, money laundering, and violating currency laws in their own native countries.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] On 4 July 2019, it was reported that Cabral told a judge that the money paid to Diack was used to buy as many as nine votes.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] Rio mayor Eduardo Paes was also accused of corruption and fraud in relation to the construction of a number of venues for the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] In 2024, Nuzman's and Cabral's conviction in this legal case was overturned by the Court.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] An outbreak of the mosquito-borne Zika virus in Brazil raised fears regarding its potential impact on athletes and visitors.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] To prevent puddles of stagnant water that allow mosquitoes to breed, organizers announced plans to perform daily inspections of Olympic venues.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] Zika virus transmission was also attributed to inefficient sewage treatment in the area, an issue that was also in the process of being addressed for the Games.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] In May 2016, a group of 150 physicians and scientists sent an open letter to the World Health Organization (WHO), calling upon them to, according to co-author Arthur Caplan, have "an open, transparent discussion of the risks of holding the Olympics as planned in Brazil".
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] The WHO dismissed the request, stating that "cancelling or changing the location of the 2016 Olympics [would] not significantly alter the international spread of Zika virus", and that there was "no public health justification" for postponing them.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] Some athletes did not attend the Games because of the epidemic.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] On 2 September 2016, however, the World Health Organization reported that there were no confirmed cases of Zika among athletes or visitors during the 2016 Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] The Guanabara Bay, whose waters were used for sailing and windsurfing competitions, is heavily polluted.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] Among the chief causes of the pollution are uncollected trash fed into the bay via polluted rivers and slums along the coast.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] Pollution of the Guanabara has been a long-term issue.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] At the Earth Summit in 1992, officials promised they would begin to address the pollution, but previous attempts to do so have been insufficient.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] As an aspect of their bid for the Games, Rio once again committed to making efforts towards cleaning the bay.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] However, some of these proposed initiatives have faced budgetary issues.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] Prior to these efforts, only 17% of Rio's sewage was treated; this raw sewage also leaked into the bay.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] Although Rio mayor Eduardo Paes stated that the city might not be able to reach its goal of having 80% of sewage treated, at least 60% of sewage was treated by March 2016, with a projected goal of 65% of sewage being treated by the start of the Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] Rio's crime problems also received renewed attention after it was awarded the 2016 Games; mayor Paes stated that the city was facing "big issues" in heightening security, but that such concerns and issues were presented to the IOC throughout the bidding process.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] The governor of Rio de Janeiro also highlighted the fact that London faced security problems, with a terrorist attack occurring just a day after it was awarded the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] The estimate was that 5,000 men of the National Public Security Force and 22,000 military officers (14,800 Army; 5,900 Navy and 1,300 of the Brazilian Air Force), in addition to the fixed quota of Rio January, would act during the Olympic Games.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] On 21 July 2016, two weeks before the scheduled start of the Games, the Brazilian Federal Police broke up an Islamic jihadist terrorist cell named Ansar al-Khilafah Brazil by arresting 12 people.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] In December 2014, media attention began growing when German broadcaster ARD reported on state-sponsored doping in Russia, comparing it to doping in East Germany.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] In November 2015, the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) published a report, and the International Association of Athletics Federations (IAAF) suspended Russia indefinitely from world track and field events.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] The United Kingdom Anti-Doping agency later assisted WADA with testing in Russia.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] In June 2016, they reported they were unable to fully carry out their work, and noted intimidation by armed Federal Security Service (FSB) agents.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] In response to these findings, WADA announced that RUSADA should be regarded as non-compliant with respect to the World Anti-Doping Code, and recommended that Russia be banned from competing in the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] The IOC rejected the recommendation, stating that the IOC and each sport's international federation would make decisions on each athlete's individual basis.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] A day before the opening ceremony, 278 athletes were cleared to compete under the Russian flag, while 111 were removed because of doping.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] In contrast, the entire Kuwaiti team was banned from competing under their own flag for a non-doping related matter.
[src:alkmaar/2016-summer-olympics-p02] Unlike the IOC, the International Paralympic Committee voted unanimously to ban the entire Russian team from the 2016 Summer Paralympics, and suspended the Russian Paralympic Committee after it found evidence that the DPM was also in operation at the 2014 Winter Paralympics.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The earliest mention of the name Alkmaar is in a 10th-century document.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] As the village grew into a town, it was granted city rights in 1254.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The oldest part of Alkmaar lies on an ancient sand bank a couple of meters (yards) above the surrounding region; it afforded some protection from inundation during medieval times.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] Its vicinage consists of some of the oldest polders in existence.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] On 24 June 1572, after the Geuzen captured the town, five Franciscans from Alkmaar were taken to Enkhuizen and hanged, becoming the martyrs of Alkmaar.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] In 1573, the city underwent a siege by Spanish forces under the leadership of Don Fadrique, son of the Duke of Alva.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The citizens sent urgent messages for help to the Prince of Orange; he responded by promising to open the floodgates of the dykes and flood the region if the need arose, which despite the protestations of the peasantry, fearful for their harvest, he proceeded to do.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] Some of his dispatches fell into the hands of Don Fadrique, and, with the waters beginning to rise, the Spaniards raised the siege and fled.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] It was a turning point in the Eighty Years War and gave rise to the expression *Bij Alkmaar begint de victorie* ("Victory begins at Alkmaar").
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The event is still celebrated every year in Alkmaar on 8 October, the day the siege ended.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] In 1799, during the French Revolutionary Wars, an Anglo-Russian expeditionary force captured the city but was ultimately defeated in the Battle of Castricum.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] After that battle, on 18 October 1799, the two opposing sides held the Convention of Alkmaar which met to determine the fate of the defeated Anglo-Russian force.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The French victory was commemorated on the Arc de Triomphe in Paris as "Alkmaer".
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The North Holland Canal, opened in 1824, was dug through Alkmaar.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] In 1865 and 1867, the railways between Alkmaar and Den Helder and between Alkmaar and Haarlem were built respectively.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] In the second half of the 20th century, Alkmaar expanded quickly with development of new neighbourhoods.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] On 1 October 1972, the town of Oudorp and the southern portions of Koedijk and Sint Pancras were added to the municipality of Alkmaar.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The municipality of Alkmaar historically consists of the following cities, towns, villages and districts: Alkmaar, Bergermeer, Daalmeer, De Hoef, De Horn, De Nollen, Het Rak, Huiswaard, Koedijk (southeastern part), Overdie, Oudorp and Omval.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] On 1 January 2015, the municipalities of Graft-De Rijp and Schermer were merged into Alkmaar.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The historical village of De Rijp is thus since a part of Alkmaar.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] These once separate villages are now all linked together by the suburban sprawl of buildings that arose between the late 1970s and early 1990s.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] During this time, the population of Alkmaar almost doubled.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The municipal council of Alkmaar consists of 39 seats, which are divided as follows after the 2026 elections.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The A9 motorway runs from Amsterdam to Alkmaar, then continues on to Den Helder as the N9.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] There are direct trains to Den Helder, Hoorn, Zaandam, Amsterdam, Utrecht, Ede, Arnhem, Nijmegen, 's-Hertogenbosch, Eindhoven, Maastricht and Haarlem.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] For exact details see Alkmaar railway station.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The waterway Noordhollandsch Kanaal, which opened in 1824, runs through Alkmaar.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] As of 2017. it can be crossed (among other ways) using two of the five operating vlotbruggen, Koedijkervlotbrug and Rekervlotbrug.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] Air travel is served by the nearest Schiphol Airport which is approximately 22 km south of Alkmaar.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] NS operates direct train services between Alkmaar and Schiphol.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] Alkmaar has many medieval buildings that are still intact, most notably the tall tower of the Grote or Sint-Laurenskerk, where many people from Alkmaar hold wedding ceremonies.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The other main attraction, especially in the summer months, is Alkmaar's cheese market at the Waagplein, one of the country's most popular tourist attractions.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The cheese market traditionally takes place from the first Friday in April through the first Friday in September.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] Every Friday morning (10:00–12:30) the Waagplein is the backdrop for this traditional cheese market.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] After the old-fashioned way of the hand clap, traders and carriers will weigh the cheeses.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] It is one of only four traditional Dutch cheese markets still in existence.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The traditional fare of this cheese market is those cheeses made in the local area, as opposed to the well-known brands of Dutch cheeses, including the Edam and Gouda cheeses.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] It is not actually possible to buy cheese at the market itself, which is really only a demonstration of how this merchants' market operated in times gone by.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] However, the demonstration, which takes place in front of the medieval weighing house, is surrounded by many specialized stalls where it is possible to buy all kinds of cheese (and non-cheese) related products.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The Waag is also home to the local tourist office and a cheese museum.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] Alkmaar has 399 registered rijksmonuments, of which most are situated along the city's old canals.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] Alkmaar has two large theatres and a big cinema (which was originally two cinemas).
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] A red light district is situated at the Achterdam, and Alkmaar has a nightlife scene as well which takes place in the pubs in front of the cheesemarket.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] Every year, at the end of May Alkmaar hosts the four-day event Alkmaar Pride, which has a canal pride parade on Saturday.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] Alkmaar is home to the professional football team AZ (Alkmaar Zaanstreek).
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] In 2006, the club moved to a new 17,000 capacity stadium, the DSB Stadion, now named the AFAS Stadion.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] In 2008–2009, AZ won the Eredivisie, the Dutch football league.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] It was the second league title for the club after the Eredivisie in 1980/81 with only one league defeat.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] Notable coaches include former FC Barcelona coach Ronald Koeman, and Netherlands national football team coach Louis van Gaal.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The city also has a velodrome where the Dutch national track cycling championships are held every year.
[src:alkmaar/alkmaar] The city hosted the 2019 European Road Championships.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The city's official name is a contraction of the (archaic) Dutch *des Hertogen bosch* ('the forest of the duke').
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The duke in question was Henry I, Duke of Brabant, whose family had owned a large estate at nearby Orthen for at least four centuries.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] He founded a new town located on some forested dunes in the middle of a marsh.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] At age 26, he granted 's-Hertogenbosch city rights and the corresponding trade privileges in 1185.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] This is the traditional date given by later chroniclers; the first mention in contemporaneous sources is 1196.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] His reason for founding the city was to protect his own interests against encroachment from Gelre and Holland; from its first days, he conceived of the city as a fortress.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It was destroyed in 1203 in a joint expedition of Gelre and Holland, but was soon rebuilt.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Some remnants of the original city walls remain.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In the late 14th century, a much larger wall was erected to protect the greatly expanded settled area.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Artificial waterways were dug to serve as a city moat, through which the rivers Dommel and Aa were diverted.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch became the birthplace and home of northern Renaissance painter Hieronymus Bosch.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Until 1520, the city flourished, becoming the second largest population centre in the territory of the present Netherlands, after Utrecht.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The city was also a center of music, and composers, such as Jheronimus Clibano, received their training at its churches.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Others held positions there: Matthaeus Pipelare was musical director at the Confraternity of Our Lady; and renowned Habsburg copyist and composer Pierre Alamire did much of his work at 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The wars of the Reformation changed the course of the city's history.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] During the Eighty Years' War, the city took the side of the Habsburg (Catholic) authorities and thwarted a Calvinist coup.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It was besieged several times by Prince Maurice of Orange, stadtholder of most of the Dutch Republic, who wanted to bring 's-Hertogenbosch under the rule of the rebel United Provinces.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The city was successfully defended against Prince Maurice in 1601 and again in 1603, but it eventually fell in the 1629 siege led by his brother Frederick Henry.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In the years of Truce, before the renewed fighting after 1618, the fortifications were greatly expanded.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The surrounding marshes made a siege of the conventional type impossible, and the fortress, deemed impregnable, was nicknamed *moerasdraak*, or the Swamp Dragon.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The town was nevertheless finally conquered by Frederik Hendrik of Orange in 1629 in a typically Dutch stratagem: he diverted the rivers Dommel and Aa, created a polder by constructing a forty-kilometre (25 mile) dyke and then pumped out the water by mills.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] After a siege of three months, the city had to surrender—an enormous blow to Habsburg geo-political strategy during the Thirty Years' War.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] This surrender cut the town off from the rest of the duchy and the area was treated by the Republic as an occupation zone without political liberties (see also Generality Lands).
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] After the Peace of Westphalia, the fortifications were again expanded.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In 1672, the Dutch *rampjaar*, the city held against the army of Louis XIV of France.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In 1794 French revolutionary troops under the command of Charles Pichegru attacked the city.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It was only weakly defended, and fell after a short siege.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Pichegru then crossed the rivers and put an end to the Dutch Republic.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Under the new Batavian Republic, established in 1795, both Catholics and *Brabanders* at last gained equal rights.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] From 1806, the city became part of the Kingdom of Holland and from 1810, it was incorporated into the First French Empire.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It was captured by the Prussians in 1814.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The next year, 1815, when the United Kingdom of the Netherlands was established, it became the capital of North Brabant.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Many newer and more modern fortresses were created in the vicinity of the city.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] A new canal was built, the 'Zuid-Willemsvaart', which gave the city an economic impulse.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Until 1878, it was forbidden to build outside the ramparts.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] That led to overcrowding and the highest infant mortality in the kingdom.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] At the end of the 19th century, the very conservative city government prevented industrial investment to avoid an increase in the number of workers and the establishment of educational institutions: students were regarded as disorderly.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] As a result, the relative importance of the city diminished.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] One of the few official Nazi concentration camp complexes in Western Europe outside Germany and Austria was named after 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It operated from January 1943, to September 1944 and was known to the Germans as Herzogenbusch (see List of subcamps of Herzogenbusch).
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] About 30,000 inmates were interned in the complex during this time, of whom about 12,000 were Jews.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In the Netherlands, this camp is known as 'Kamp Vught', because the concentration camp was actually located at a heath near Vught, a village a few kilometres south of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The city was occupied by German forces during World War II from 1940 to 1944.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The railway station was bombed by planes of the Royal Air Force on 16 September 1944.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The city was liberated between 24 and 27 October 1944 during Operation Pheasant by British soldiers of Major-General Robert Knox Ross's 53rd (Welsh) Infantry Division following the victory of the 1st Battalion, East Lancashire Regiment, of 158th Infantry Brigade over the enemy on 23–24 October.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] After the war, 's-Hertogenbosch was modernized, like many other cities in the Netherlands.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It was possible that it was only the geography that shielded the old town from rigorous reconstruction in those early years.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Just in time, the pendulum swung back to protecting the history of the city.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In 1956, the council wanted to demolish the Moriaan, the oldest brick building in the Netherlands, to give traffic better access to the market square.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The permit was refused by the government and instead the building was restored, starting in 1963.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Later, city councils became much more aware of the value of historic buildings and from about the turn of the millennium, the historic fortifications are also given much attention by the authorities.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The population centres in the municipality are: Bokhoven, Crevecoeur, Deuteren (former village), Dieskant, Empel, Engelen, Gewande, 's-Hertogenbosch, Hintham, Kruisstraat, Maliskamp, Meerwijk, Orthen (former village), Oud-Empel, and Rosmalen.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Climate in this area has mild differences between highs and lows, and there is adequate rainfall year-round.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The Köppen Climate Classification subtype for this climate is "Cfb" (Marine West Coast Climate/Oceanic climate).
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The city of 's-Hertogenbosch has become a center of industry, education, administration and culture.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It is currently the fourth city of North Brabant.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It is home to many national and international businesses such as Heineken, Epic, Tyco International, SAP and many others.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The Jeroen Bosch Hospital is the biggest employer in the area, with over 4,000 employees.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] There are also over 350 restaurants, pubs and cafés to be found in the city.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is also home to the European Ceramic Work Centre.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] This is a juried international ceramic residency where they invite artists, designers and architects from around to the world to explore the medium of Ceramics.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] This program was initially started in 1991 and continues to this day.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The city has its own food speciality, the Bossche Bol—effectively a giant profiterole, somewhat larger than a tennis ball, which is filled with whipped cream and coated with chocolate.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The spoken language is Maaslands (the variant spoken in 's-Hertogenbosch is called *Bosch* which is placed among the Central North Brabantian dialects, although other classification systems also describe it as East Brabantian), which is very similar to colloquial Dutch.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] De Toonzaal is a music venue for chamber music, improvised music, and experimental music.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] For popular music there is the venue W2 (or Willem II).
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The Noordbrabants Museum is a provincial museum with an overview of works that Vincent van Gogh made in Brabant.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The Design Museum Den Bosch is a modern art museum.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The Jheronimus Bosch Art Center, is dedicated to the work of Hieronymus Bosch.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Other museums include the Swan Brothers' House and Museum Slager.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Also the National (Dutch) Carnavalsmuseum Oeteldonks gemintemuzejum is located in the city.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In the near future a new museum will be opened about the fortresses of the town and in general in Europe.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The house where the famous painter Hieronymus produced his paintings can be visited on the market square.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has a strong carnival tradition.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In its current form the story and symbolism dates from 1881 to 1883.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In these years some citizens created the legend of "Oeteldonk", whereby the city was renamed to Oeteldonk for the three day carnival.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] "Donk" is a reference to a dry place in the marsh.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The frog is widely used as a symbol during the 's-Hertogenbosch Carnival.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It is also a symbol of the Oeteldonk marsh.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It was also a remark aimed at Bishop Godschalk from Den Dungen, where 'Van den Oetelaar' was a common family name.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] He had wanted to forbid the traditional festivities of Shrove Tuesday that often led to excesses.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Oeteldonk is a village and therefore every inhabitant is a farmer or a '*durske*' (a girl or young woman), eliminating class differences.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The village is headed by the Mayor "Peer vaan den Muggenheuvel tot den Bobberd".
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Each year the mayor of 's-Hertogenbosch hands over his authority to the Mayor of Oeteldonk.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] On Sunday at 11:11 AM the Mayor of Oeteldonk then receives Prince Carnaval "Prince Amadeiro XXVI" at Oeteldonk central station.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] From there a parade of all carnival clubs escorts the company to the town hall.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The citizens of 's-Hertogenbosch wear traditional outfits throughout these days.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] A so-called *boerenkiel* is worn and every year patches are designed according to that years theme which can then be stitched onto the outfit.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The *boerenkiel* is often combined with a traditional farmers bandana and a long scarf in the colors of Oeteldonk.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The tradition of the Boerenkiel and / or Bandana is very different from the carnival traditions in the rest of the Netherlands.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Other aspects like the parade, the temporary name and the temporary flag (for Oeteldonk red, white and yellow) are very similar.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch was founded as a fortified city and that heritage can still be seen today.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] After World War II, plans were made to modernise the old city, by filling in the canals, removing or modifying some ramparts and redeveloping historic neighbourhoods.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Before these plans could come to effect, the central government declared the city a protected townscape.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Most historic elements have been preserved.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In contrast to cities like Rotterdam, 's-Hertogenbosch also survived the Second World War relatively unscathed.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Much of its historic heritage remains intact, and today there are always renovations going on in the city to preserve the many old buildings, fortifications, churches and statues for later generations.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The city center has a cosy atmosphere because of the almost continuous ramparts that still surround it.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It has been molded by the multiple rivers that convene on 's-Hertogenbosch, giving the center its strange street plan so different from the usual grid plan where streets meet at right angles.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The center is dominated by Saint John's Cathedral (*Sint-Janskathedraal* in Dutch), which dates from c.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] 1220 and is best known for its Brabantine Gothic design and the many sculptures of craftsmen that are sitting on almost every arc and rim along the outside of the cathedral.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In 2010 an extensive restoration was completed, undoing the damage of many years of wear-and-tear and acid rain.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] On the central square is the oldest remaining brick house of the Netherlands, 'de Moriaan', which was built at the beginning of the 13th century.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In the 1960s, de Moriaan was renovated to its former glory based on a famous 16th-century Dutch painting called 'De Lakenmarkt van 's-Hertogenbosch' ('The fabric market of 's-Hertogenbosch').
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The town hall is an original 14th-century Gothic building.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] After the town was conquered by the Dutch Republic in 1629, it received a new facade in the style of Dutch Baroque architecture.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It showcased the authority of the new masters, just like the new town hall in Maastricht would.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Hidden below the old city is a canal network called the Binnendieze, which once spanned 22 km (14 mi).
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It started out as a regular river, the Dommel, running through the city in medieval times.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Due to a lack of space in the city, people started building their houses and roads over the river.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Later, the Binnendieze functioned as a sewer and fell into disrepair.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In recent decades, the remaining sixth part of the old waterway system has been renovated, and it is possible to take several guided subterranean boat trips through it.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has an extensive and almost complete fifteenth-to-seventeenth-century city fortification.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It was made to profit from the city's strong defensive position, lying on a sandy hill in the center of a large swamp fed by many rivers.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] This also caused the main ramparts to be preserved, because they were crucial in keeping out the water.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In 2004 the city was awarded the title *European Fortress City of the year*.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In the years that followed it restored many of the city defenses to much of their old glory.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Apart from small sections of medieval walls, the main structure of the fortification is a late-medieval (fifteenth-century) wall.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The upper sections were removed when cannon became more powerful, and polygonal bastions were added, some after the conquest by the republic.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Most of these have not been restored to their original height, but do maintain their brick walls.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The citadel in the north west of the city does retain its original height.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Around the city itself many other fortresses can still be seen.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In the north east of the old city, the hexagonal gunpowder magazine, called *Kruithuis* is located close to the citadel.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It is one of only a handful that still exist in the Netherlands, and was built when the city was still part of the Spanish Netherlands.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It is planned to become the museum of fortress 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] One of the bastions of the fortress now houses the mini museum Bastionder.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It has been dug out in a bastion of the south side.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] On the inside it shows a unique wrought iron cannon, and an older bastion that was walled in by the current one.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] On the south side of the city, the city center and walls still border the Bossche Broek, an old polder that could never be made dry.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In 1995 the dyke of the Dommel broke and an enormous amount of water entered the polder.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It also flooded and blocked the main Dutch highway A2.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In order to prevent this in the future, the area was rearranged to store excess water in case of emergencies.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In 2006 the area had been furnished with higher dikes and locks that allowed a controlled flooding of the polder and some adjacent areas in case of emergency.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The Bossche Broek is now a 22-hectare (54-acre) nature reserve, that stretches all the way to Vught.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It is connected to the Moerputten and Vlijmens Ven, with which it forms a Natura 2000 area.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Rare species in the area are the scarce large blue and the European weather loach.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The Moerputten sports the Moerputten Bridge, a 600-metre (650 yard) long nineteenth century railway bridge and engineering feat.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] What is unique about the area is its close proximity to the city center.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The city is also the location of the *Bolwoningen* complex, an array of fifty experimental spherical houses designed by Dries Kreijkamp.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The Lutheran Church, 's-Hertogenbosch is no longer used as a church.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The city has one professional football club, FC Den Bosch.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It is the 1967 successor of the professional branches of BVV (Bossche Voetbal Vereniging) and Wilhelmina.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Both of them still exist as amateur football clubs.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] As a successor of BVV FC Den Bosch can claim the national championship of 1948.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] This championship led to the construction of stadium De Vliert, which at one time had a capacity of 30,000.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Due to the less successful years that followed, the capacity is now only 8,500 visitors.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] FC Den Bosch was the first club of Dutch international player Ruud van Nistelrooy.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is more successful in field hockey.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The women's team in particular is a dominant force in the Dutch field hockey competition.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The professional basketball club Heroes Den Bosch is also very successful.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The city's rugby club is called The Dukes and dates from 1974.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It is located at a very scenic location at the foot of the city walls.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Because of the limited space, the club plays on artificial turf and part of the accommodation is subterranean.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It became the national rugby champion in 2008.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] As regards events the city is host to the Rosmalen Grass Court Championships, a combined ATP Tour and WTA Tour grass court tennis event played two weeks before the Wimbledon Championships.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The World Archery Championships and World Para Archery Championship were held here in June 2019.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] During these combined World Championships two separate venues were used: the Parade and the rugby fields of The Dukes.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] All finals took place in the arena at the Parade.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The Parade is a historic square surrounded by high trees, situated at the foot of the nearly seven-hundred-year-old Saint John's Cathedral in the attractive center of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The Zuid-Willemsvaart runs from the Meuse just north of the city towards Maastricht via Helmond and Weert.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In 's-Hertogenbosch it runs through the city proper, south east from where a bastion has been cut off from the citadel.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Because of this route it was impossible to widen it further than for ships of CEMT class II.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Therefore, the Máxima Canal of 8 km (5 miles) was dug just east of the city, creating a shortcut from the canal to the Meuse suitable for ships of CEMT class IV.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] On the remaining part of the Zuid-Willemsvaart west of the city is the industrial harbor of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is situated on the busy A2 motorway, the most important north–south connection of the Netherlands.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] This connection was established with the opening of the Dieze Bridge in 1942.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] From 1961 the Utrecht-'s-Hertogenbosch section was 2 times 2 lanes.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In 1970 the A2 was rerouted to the east of the city.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In 1989 it finally became a controlled-access highway.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In 1996 the section between 's-Hertogenbosch and Eindhoven became a controlled-access highway.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The situation in Maastricht was only solved in 2016, when the Koning Willem-Alexandertunnel was opened.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] On the east–west axis 's-Hertogenbosch is on the A59 motorway.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The A65 motorway between 's-Hertogenbosch and Tilburg is a regional highway, but is not completely access-controlled.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch railway station is on the Utrecht–Boxtel part of the railway stretch between Amsterdam and the Dutch industrial/tech center near Eindhoven.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] As a consequence north–south trains depart every ten minutes.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] On the Tilburg–Nijmegen railway trains run on a more modest schedule.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch railway station is also a major station for Arriva buslines that serve the city and most of its suburbs.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Other stations within the limits of the municipality are 's-Hertogenbosch Oost railway station and Rosmalen railway station.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Vught railway station is actually closer to the city center than that in Rosmalen.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has attempted to adapt to the growing popularity of the bicycle in Dutch cities.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] A reasonable amount of bike paths has so far been constructed in the town.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In 2011, the city was chosen as *Fietsstad 2011*—the top bike city of the Netherlands for 2011.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] This is a big achievement for a city where bicycle use is lower than in the rest of the Netherlands".
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has multiple vocational universities called *Hogeschool* in Dutch.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The HAS Hogeschool of about 3,500 students is focused on agricultural and food technology.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Avans Hogeschool is located in 's-Hertogenbosch and two nearby cities.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Joost is an art academy that is now part of Avans and dates back to 1812.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Fontys Hogeschool also offers some education in the city.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The Jheronimus Academy of Data Science (JADS), located at the Mariënburg Campus in the center of 's-Hertogenbosch, and provides a number of data science programs at graduate (MSc) and post-graduate level (PhD).
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It is a department of the Eindhoven University of Technology and Tilburg University.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] In secondary education the City Gymnasium is a gymnasium (school) that originated from the Latin school of the city.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It is comparable to a grammar school and can trace its origin back 1274.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The same type of education and all other types of secondary education are offered by a number of large institutes.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Roman Catholicism is the dominant religion in 's-Hertogenbosch, with somewhat more than 40% of the population counting themselves as belonging to it.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Even so, attendance at mass is significantly lower than 40%.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Three churches in the city center are still in use by the Catholic church: Saint John's Cathedral, Saint Catherine and the Monastery Church of the Franciscans nearby the railway station.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] Smaller churches in use by the Roman Catholic church are: Saint Anne's Church in Hintham, Saint Landoline Church in Empel, Saint Willibrord Church in Maaspoort, Saint Lambert Church (Rosmalen), etc.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The Protestant religion has seen its share of believers in the city fall from 20% to about 4%.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The Eastern Orthodox Church is a new church in town.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] It is based at Saint Catherine's Church where Catholic worship services have been held again since 2021.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The Arrahma Mosque has been built by the Moroccan community.
[src:alkmaar/s-hertogenbosch] The Turkish community has the Orhan Gazi Mosque.
